Commentary.Commentary: We are back. The final session is set to begin. The Australian players take the field.
... Day 2, Session 3 ...

What a collapse this has been for Australia. Pakistan have surely crawled their way back into this Test match by picking up 5 wickets in the post-Lunch session. Pakistan would’ve planned to come and use the cracks to their benefit. Nauman Ali did just that and broke a crucial sixth-wicket stand. Later, it was just a magical spell by Naseem Shah and Shaheen Afridi that got Pakistan back into the game. Both the bowlers picked up four-fers. Pakistan would be happy to restrict Australia under 400 runs here. So, early Tea has been taken on Day 2. In the post-Tea session, Pakistan will come out to bat and would hope to get off to a solid start. The final session starts at 1505 IST (0935 GMT). Do join us to see how things pan out.

OUT! Cleaned up! Shaheen Afridi picks up his fourth wicket and that will be the end of the Australian innings. Afridi switches to 'round the wicket and hurls across a yorker on middle stump. It is just too quick for Mitchell Swepson to keep out and the ball sneaks under the willow to hit the base of middle stump. This has been a roaring come back from the Pakistani pacers and they have bundle out Australia for 392 runs!
FOUR! And again! This time to the right of gully. Banged in short and going across off stump. Swepson hangs back and dabs it past the fielder at gully for another boundary.
Edged and four! This is sliding across the off stump. Mitchell Swepson hangs back and pushes at it. The ball goes off the outside edge and in between the slip cordon and gully for a boundary.
Pitched up, around off at over 140 clicks and reversing into the batter. Pat Cummins does well to keep it out.
Sliding into middle and leg. Cummins defends it out solidly.
Around off, played towards cover-point and Pat Cummins wants the single. They do scamper through eventually.
Length ball, angling into leg stump and keeping a bit low. Swepson gets pushed onto the back foot but does well to get his blade on it.
Very full, curving back in from outside off. Mitchell Swepson does well to dig it out on the off side.

Full length, angled down leg. Pat Cummins leaves it alone.
Full and outside off, Cummins looks to hammer it across but misses.
Mitchell Swepson is the last man in.

OUT! BOWLED! Nothing better than a full ball coming back into the tailender and it is just too quick for Nathan Lyon. Naseem Shah bends his back this time and goes full and at the stumps at 144.5 kph. The ball nips back in sharply and richocets off Lyon's pads before hitting the middle stump. This has truly been a brilliant performance from the young pacer and with just one wicket remaining in the innings, he probably deserves to get that elusive five-wicket haul.
Tailing in from around off. Lyon stays solid in defense.
FOUR! Nathan Lyon is off the mark in style! A bit too straight from Shah and it is flicked away through backward square leg for a boundary.
Fuller this time, tailing back into off stump. Pat Cummins hangs back and does well to get a bat on it. The ball goes off the edge and down towards third man. They get a single.
Pitched up, on off. Cummins pushes it towards mid off and looks for the single that isn't there.
On off, a hint of reverse away from the batter. Cummins edges it down with soft hands towards gully.

It is full, outside off, tailing in a bit, at 142 clicks. Mitchell Starc ends up chipping it in front of mid off. Nauman Ali charges in and takes a sharp catch diving forward. Also, in the mini-contest between Afridi and Shah. The score is 3-3.

OUT! LBW! Alex Carey holes out on 67. His valiant knock comes to an end. Just in the last over, one of the one-air commentators said that he is confident of both these batters racking up their first Test tons here. Well, the commentators curse has struck yet again. It is tossed up, outside off. The ball grips and turns in off the deck. Alex Carey is rooted inside the crease and gets struck on the pads, as he fails to defend it out. Nauman Ali appeals for lbw and the umpire raises his finger in a flash. Alex Carey has a chat with his partner and decides to take the review. The review goes Pakistan's way, while Carey has only one way to go, that is to the pavilion.

Well, it looks plumb but at the last moment, Alex Carey has reviewed it. The third umpire checks UltraEdge and finds no edge on it. Ball Tracker takes some time to build up but finally shows up with three reds and Carey has to walk back. OUT!

We are back for the post-Lunch session! The umpires are followed by Pakistan players onto the field. Cameron Green and Alex Carey walk back out and take guard. It's going to be Hasan Ali to start proceedings with the ball after the interval. Let's go...

Right then! There are more and more cracks opening up in the pitch and this indicates that sooner or later, spin will play an important role in the Test match. Australia seem to be in control at the moment and another decent session will see them have complete control of the match. Pakistan will have to bowl a lot better and make sure they don't concede more than 400 runs, which doesn't seem likely at the moment and that could be a dangerous sign for them. The second session starts at 1310 IST (0740 GMT). Do join us then.

One must have thought that the hosts would get at least a couple of wickets in the first session if not more and look to keep the opposition down to a score of in and around the 300-run mark. This hasn't been the case though as they have not been able to pick up a single wicket and have conceded runs at a hemorrhaging rate. The only spark was provided by their best bowler in the match, Naseem Shah who's second spell of the day gave us a good glimpse of him reversing the ball both ways and troubling the batters. Shaheen Afridi too tried his best to reverse it but just couldn't get enough purchase to trouble the opposition batters. The hosts need to pull up their socks in the upcoming session to get back into the game.

Session summary : 28 overs / 88 runs / 0 wickets. This has been a session that has completely belonged to the visitors. Alex Carey and Cameron Green have just looked so solid at the crease and along with that, they came out with positive intent as the scoring rate significantly improved from yesterday. Both batters have surpassed the individual 50-run mark and will now look to continue the same in the post-Lunch session as well. Australia will now look to target 400 runs which on this surface can be a really good score, given the reverse swing coming into play. The visitors will be mightily pleased with that session.

Drinks! Well, it's been a fascinating first hour of play on Day 2. Both Alex Carey and Cameron Green have looked good and have added 47 runs to the overnight total in 13 overs. Shaheen and Naseem haven't got much purchase from the second new ball yet and the ball seems to be coming onto the bat nicely. Nauman Ali and Hasan Ali though have just started to create a bit of doubt in the batters' minds. This ball has just started to reverse a bit and it will be interesting to see if the Aussie batters at the crease can carry on until the Lunch break.

What happened here? That is one of the most bizarre things one will see in a game of cricket! Hasan Ali bowls a perfect slower yorker, angled into off. Alex Carey looks to flick but gets beaten and there is an appeal for caught behind. The finger is raised straightaway but Carey reviews it. The umpires then themselves go to third umpire, so whether it was given caught behind or LBW is confusing. Anyways, the replay shows that the ball missed the bat, the pads as well and popped up off the surface, clipped the off stump and went to Mohammad Rizwan on the bounce. After all that, it is just a dot ball!

A bit of confusion. It has been given out as caught behind and Alex Carey reviews it straightaway. The umpires then come together and check for the bump ball and the soft signal is out which means it's an umpire review and not Australia's review. On first replay, there seems to be no bat involved and the same is confirmed by UltraEdge. Surprisingly there's no pad involved as well. The ball misses everything and flicks the off stump but the bails don't come off.

The morning session on Day 2 is set to begin. The Pakistan playes begin to walk out on the field. Followed by Alex Carey and Cameron Green who walk out with the swords. It will be Naseem Shah to start with the ball. Here we go...

A truly deserved outing for the hosts. It was Shaheen Afridi who started the proceeding but later it was Naseem Shah who stood out and justified his selection into the side. The young pacer showed great skills, by moving the ball in both directions with no drop in pace. From his 19 overs, Shah bowled 9 maidens and has been very economical. Pakistan would hope he continues the good work on Day 2 with a fairly new ball in play. The first hour of the session will give you the gist of how this day would pan out. Do not go anywhere.

It was all about Australia except the starting period of the morning session and the final hour of the third session. It was Smith and Khawaja in particular, who built a solid stand of 138 runs and completed the repair work after losing two early wickets in the third over. Although, once Smith fell, there was a collapse that took place and Australia were left with five wickets in hand on Day 1. Alex Carey and Cameron Green hold the key for the visitors and they would be eyeing the 300-run mark, atleast.

Hello and a warm welcome to all! It is the second day of this third Test match between Pakistan and Australia and boy, hasn't this Test match moved along in full swing. This is the only time we saw 5 wickets fall on the first day in this series. A result looks likely at the moment.
... Day 2, Session 1 ...

Right then! 34 overs were bowled in the final session with Australia scoring 87 runs but losing 3 wickets as well. At 232/5, the first session on Day 2 is set up really nicely and it will be interesting to see as to which team can get ahead in the match. The action on Day 2 will begin at 1030 IST (0500 GMT). Do join us then. Cheers!

Shaheen Afridi is up for a quick chat. He starts by thanking the Almighty. Mentions, he tries to bowl full and find early wickets for his side. Adds that, as the wickets haven’t been helpful for the pacers in the past two matches. So, as bowlers, they just aimed to hit the right lengths.

The visitors made a horrific start and had a terrible final hour as well. Between all this, they looked comfortable for a long while though. Well, two people looked comfortable, Usman Khawaja and Steven Smith. Warner and Marnus Labuschagne fell cheaply in the third over, pushing Australia on the back foot. Khawaja and Smith steadied the ship and then put away the bad deliveries consistently as both of them reached the individual 50-run mark. With the partnership well over a hundred, Smith played across the line and got out. This opened the floodgates for the opposition and an out-of-form Travis Head couldn't stay on the crease for long. Khawaja too fell eventually, nine short of what would have been yet another brilliant hundred. Alex Carey and especially Cameron Green showed good resilience in the end to ensure that they didn't lose further wickets and it will all be about getting through the first session for them on day 2.

Pakistani star bowler, Shaheen Afridi gave them more than a perfect start as he got rid of David Warner and Marnus Labuschagne in the space of three deliveries. After that though, they couldn't press the issue further and slowly but surely started leaking runs as well. Hasan Ali looked out of touch early on, bowling no balls in almost every single over but bowled well later in the day. Both spinners too weren't of much use for a long time but Sajid Khan did hold up one end and even got a wicket. The pick of the bowlers was Naseem Shah who was brought back into the side and he exploited the slightly older ball really well, getting it to reverse. They still couldn't pick up wickets though until the start of the final session when Shah dismissed Smith. They kept on probing and in the final hour of play, the hosts got two more wickets, including the big wicket of Khawaja. A good first session on the second day might see them bundle out the Aussies for less than 300 which could make things really interesting.

Brilliant ebb and flow to this Test match on the very first day but it's the hosts who have roared back late in the day to get into the driving seat. This is the most number of wickets that have fallen on the first day in the whole series and Pakistan will be pretty pleased with their effort. This was also the third slowest run rate for Australia in the first innings of a Test match in the last 10 years. This tells you that the pitch had more in it for the bowlers than everyone initially thought.

Session summary : 30 overs - 75 runs - 0 wickets. It's been all Australia since the double blow from Shaheen Afridi in the 3rd over of the innings. The second session has flown by and there haven't been almost any signs of Steven Smith or Usman Khawaja faltering. Both of them have frustrated the Pakistani bowlers and surpassed the individual fifty-run mark as well.. Early in the session, Afridi did get it to reverse and then midway through the session, Naseem Shah too bowled a probing spell but it's been mostly the spinners who have bowled. Neither Nauman Ali nor Sajid Khan have created enough opportunities for the hosts and it's been really comfortable going for the two Aussie batters. The visitors have gone from a position of misery to a position of real promise now. Pakistan need atleast a couple of wickets in the final session or Australia might be looking at a score of 400 plus on the second day. The final session will begin at 1530 IST (1000 GMT). Do join us then.

Pakistan put up a dominating performance with the new ball. It was Shahid Afridi who worked his magic and struck twice in only his second over to send back Warner and Labuschagne. Later, Pakistan could’ve tightened the screws, only if the players had held on to the catches. Nauman Ali went for aplenty, he dropped Steven Smith at 19 of his own bowling. It was a tough chance though. Pakistan would come back and look to take some early wickets in this session as well. But it won't easy task, as Steven Smith and Usman Khawaja seem to have their eye in. Do join us at 1310 IST (0740 GMT) to find out how things pan out in the afternoon session.

So, it was a tough start to the innings for Australia. After electing to bat first, Australia lost two early wickets in the form of David Warner and Marnus. Australia were reeling at 8/2 inside three overs. Steven Smith and Usman Khawaja had their task cut out. With some rub of green by their side, Australia managed to remain unscathed till the Lunch break. The pair stitched a solid partnership of 62 runs and would hope to continue their good work when they come out again.

What an intriguing first session Test cricket did we witness in Lahore! 24 overs of play with 2 wickets and 70 runs. We lacked this in the past Test matches, which mostly saw the batters dominate the proceedings. The story can remain the same here, although with some tinge of green and some cracks on the deck, make it interesting. Pakistan dominated the first hour of play, while the third-wicket stand for Australia got them back into the game.

Length ball, on middle and leg. Usman Khawaja defends it back to the bowler.
Outside off, left alone.
Short ball, around middle and leg. Blocked out by Usman Khawaja.

FOUR! Steven Smith gets his third boundary of the innings. Good expansion of arms. Full length, wide outside off. Steven Smith does not shy away. He expands his arms and creams it through covers for a glorious boundary.
Two dots in a row! Good length, outside off. Steven Smith shuffles across and shoulders his arms at it.
On a length, outside off. Smith prods to defends it out solidly.
Back of a length, outside off. Usman Khawaja rides the bounce really well and punches it through cover-point for three runs.
Fuller, outside off. Usman Khawaja defends it to point.
Length ball, on the stumps. Usman Khawaja blocks it back to the bowler.
Four dots in a row to end the over! Full length, outside off, it nips in a touch. Steven Smith gets an inside edge on his pads, before it rolls out to the off side.
Fuller, on the fifth stump line. Steven Smith presses forward to defend it into the deck.
Full length, outside off. Steven Smith shuffles across to defend it out solidly.
Length, on off. Smith defends it out solidly.
FOUR! Steven Smith growing with confidence with each shot. Full length, on the pads. Steven Smith flicks it through square leg for a boundary.
Fuller, on the stumps. Smith eases it to mid on.
Outside off, left alone by Usman Khawaja.
Full length, on middle and leg. Steven Smith flicks it to right of mid on. Nauman Ali dives to that side to make a sharp stop. The batters take a single.
Smith is no happy with the movement behind the bowler's arm. He leaves a length ball, outside off and shows his frustration instantly.
FOUR! Classic Steven Smith! Overpitched, just outside off. Steven Smith drives it past mid off on the front foot. It races away to the fence.
Full length, across the right-hander. Steven Smith has no interest in chasing this one.
Fuller, on off. Smith flicks it to mid-wicket.
Fuller, on off. Usman Khawaja defends it to cover. Just 2 runs off the over. Hasan Ali continues his good work.

BEATEN! On a length, pitching around off and shapes away a touch off the deck. Usman Khawaja is enticed to play away from his body. He goes hunting, only to ge beaten on the outside edge. Ali bowling in the right channel here.
Full length, outside off. Usman Khawaja drives it to cover.
Length, down leg. Usman Khawaja shows no interest.
Good length, shaping across the left-hander. Usman Khawaja leaves it alone for the keeper.
Full length, on off. Usman Khawaja drives it down the ground. The batters take two to long off.

A huge appeal for LBW but turned down! A length ball, on off, this one holds its line. Steven Smith shuffles across and tries to defend it out but misses. He gets rapped on his pads, but clearly outside the line.
Steven Smith comes in at number 4.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! This is another short stay for Marnus Labuschagne at the crease in this series. Shaheen Afridi is runnning riots with the ball here. He picks up his second wicket of the over. Pakistan on top of proceedings within just three overs of play. It is a full-length delivery, outside off, shaping across the right-hander. Marnus Labuschagne goes flirting away from his body. The ball takes the outside edge and Mohammad Rizwan does the rest behind the sticks.
Commentary.Howout: c Mohammad Rizwan b Shaheen Afridi

Commentary.Commentary: Touch short, on middle and leg. Marnus Labuschagne defends it to the right of the bowler.
Marnus Labuschagne is the new man in.

OUT! LBW! Shaheen Afridi strikes and Pakistan get a very early wicket. It is a length ball, pitching on off. It nips in a long way off the deck. David Warner stays inside the crease, tries to defend it out but fails to get any blade on it. He gets beaten by the movement to get pinged on his pads. Shaheen Afridi appeals and the umpire raises his fingers in a flash. David Warner walks down the track, has a chat with Usman Khawaja, but decides to continue his walk to the pavilion. A dream start for Pakistan with the ball.
Full, on the stumps. Warner defends it out.
A short ball, on off. Usman Khawaja tucks it to fine leg for a single. He gets off the mark here.
Good work by Mohammad Rizwan behind the sticks. Full length, sliding down the leg side. Warner does not chase it, while Mohammad Rizwan dives to his right to make a sharp stop.

FOUR! David Warner gets the first boundary off the innings but in a fortunate manner. Good length, outside off. David Warner tries to cut it away. It goes past the keeper and races away to the fine leg fence off the bottom edge.
Make it fout on the trot! Ali serves it on a length, on the stumps. Warner stays behind and defends it to the off side.
Three dots in a row to start with! Full length, on middle and leg. David Warner flicks it to left of mid on.
This one carries! Good length, outside off, shaping across. Mohammad Rizwan moves to his left to gather the ball.
A length ball, outside off, shaping across the left-hander. The ball dies as it reaches the keeper.
Hasan Ali to bowl from the other end.
Full length, outside off. Usman Khawaja taps it to point.
Full length, on the pads. Warner works it to fine leg for one.
Shaheen Afridi bangs in a short ball, on the bodyline. This one flies off the deck. David Warner is taken by surprise, as he defends it aerially towards short leg. It falls short.
Good length, outside off. Warner leaves it alone.
A bit too straight now. Full and on the stumps. Warner stays back and clips it through mid-wicket for a brace. Australia and David Warner are off the mark here!
A full-length ball, on middle and leg. David Warner defends it out solidly. Shaheen Afridi starts on the money.

We are ready for play! The umpires are out in the middle and so are the Pakistani players. They are followed by the Australian opening pair of Usman Khawaja and David Warner. Shaheen Afridi has the new ball in hand and is raring to go. Let's play...

Pat Cummins is up for a chat. He says that the conditions look similar to those of the first two Tests and hence they will have a bat first. Adds that spinners will come into play on days 4 and 5 and hopes they can make full use of it. Babar Azam the captain of Pakistan says that they would have liked to bat first as well. He adds that the spinners will have a say on the third or fourth day and informs that they have made one change with Naseem Shah coming in for Faheem Ashraf.

Australia (Unchanged XI) - David Warner, Usman Khawaja, Marnus Labuschagne, Steven Smith, Travis Head, Cameron Green, Alex Carey (WK), Mitchell Starc, Pat Cummins (C), Mitchell Swepson and Nathan Lyon.

Pakistan (Playing XI) - Abdullah Shafique, Imam-ul-Haq, Azhar Ali, Babar Azam(C), Fawad Alam, Mohammad Rizwan(WK), Sajid Khan, Hasan Ali, Nauman Ali, Shaheen Afridi and Naseem Shah (In for Faheem Ashraf).
TOSS - Up goes the flip of the coin and it lands in Australia's favour. They have elected to BAT first.

Pakistan looked to be heading towards defeat within three and a half days' play but they certainly turned it around in the final innings. Generally, days 4 and 5 are the most difficult to bat on but just like Rawalpindi, the playing surface in Karachi didn't have much in it for the bowlers but it still took a monumental effort from skipper Babar Azam and a couple of others to see the hosts through the final day. Will we see a winner in the series? Or will it be another run-fest that will end in a draw? All eyes on the opening session. But first, toss and team news coming up in a bit.

The Aussies were in full control of the second Test match for three innings but in the final innings, they let the chance of winning the match slip out of their hands. They almost pulled it off though late on Day 5 when the GOAT, Nathan Lyon got some crucial wickets which made things really nervy for the hosts. Their batting has been solid throughout the series so far and with a slightly better bowling performance, they might just be able to get a famous away series victory.

The series is still wide open and we are at the Gaddafi Stadium in Lahore for the 3rd and final Test match between Pakistan and Australia. Incidentally, Lahore is hosting it's first Test match since 2009. Two Test matches have flown by and only the visitors have looked likely to enforce a result in their favour, that too only in the second match. All eyes will be on the surface and how will it play out as the match progresses. On that note, welcome to the coverage.
... MATCH DAY ...
Welcome back! Around 3 overs left in the day's play as David Warner and Usman Khawaja walk out to build on Australia's lead. Shaheen Afridi is getting ready. Here we go...
... THIRD INNINGS ...

Pat Cummins finished with a 5-wicket haul and is leading his team off the park. His partner in crime, Mitchell Starc, bagged a 4-fer. A placard in the crowd read - Mitchell Starc, you beauty - Pat Cummins, you cutie! Ahem. Beast would have been a better choice of word. Anyway, Australia will have to bat for a few overs before Stumps and with a big lead under their belt, they will be confident of seeing off the day's play safely. Stay tuned...

A collapse of epic proportions! All seemed hunky-dory for Pakistan in the first hour after Tea but then Pat Cummins decided to unleash Mitchell Starc. He repaid the faith shown in him by the skipper and got rid of Fawad Alam and that opened the floodgates. Pakistan slipped from 248/3 to 268 all out and have ended up conceding a 123-run lead which can be considered quite hefty on this surface. The hosts will be disappointed as they worked really hard in the two sessions with Azhar Ali and Abdullah Shafique forming a big stand and then Babar Azam extending it further but this collapse has left them reeling.

OUT! TIMBER! Mitchell Starc cleans up Naseem Shah and Pakistan have been bundled out for 268! Starc serves a brilliant yorker that tails in late into the off stump. The pace and the reverse swing is just too much to handle for the number 11 batter and Shah can only watch back as the bails come off. The ball crashes into the base of off stump and Pakistan have collapsed from a position of strength! Mitchell Starc picks up 4 wickets and Australia have just steamrolled the Pakistani tail.
Beaten! A touch short and on off, Naseem is squared up in defense and it whistles past the outside edge.
Starc spears it full and outside off, Naseem pushes at it and misses.
Naseem Shah is the last batsman.

OUT! LBW! Mitchell Starc goes wide of the crease and angles it into middle and leg. Babar Azam looks to work it through mid-wicket but the ball skids through and Azam falls over a bit in his stance. He gets rapped on the pads and there is a huge appeal. The finger is raised in a jiffy and Babar Azam has no option other than to review the LBW decision at this stage. Babar seems to be caught plumb in front but given the angle of the delivery, it might be missing leg slightly. UltraEdge shows no bat is involved and Ball Tracking shows that the ball is going to clip the leg stump. Azam goes after a well-compiled knock and Starc has his third wicket.
Angled in full and on off, from 'round the stumps. Afridi does well to make the block.
Shaheen Afridi's turn to face the music.

OUT! TAKEN! A 5-WICKET HAUL FOR CUMMINS! Pat Cummins becomes the first pacer in the series to pick up a fifer and boy hasn't he deserved it today! Cummins pitches it up, a bit outside off. Hasan Ali leans in and looks to push it out towards covers. The ball reverses away from the right-hander this time and the ball goes off the face of the bat towards first slip. Steven Smith has had a mixed bag in the slips but takes a sharp low catch this time. Cummins is too good for the Pakistani lower order and Australia are a couple of wickets away from wrapping up things in the first innings.
Commentary.Howout: c Steven Smith b Pat Cummins

Commentary.Commentary: A bit shorter, close to the off stump. Ali keeps it out on the off side.
Fullish delivery, around off and tailing in late. Hasan Ali does really well to keep it out.
On a good length, reversing into Ali from around off. Blocked out.
Hasan Ali is the new batter. Pakistan trail by 123 runs. The lightmeter has been handed to Aleem Dar. He though has not taken any reading as of now.

OUT! Nauman Ali reviewed the decision for an LBW decision but to no avail. Pat Cummins is on a marauding spell at the moment as he picks up his fourth wicket. Cummins comes from 'round the wicket and serves it on a length close to the off pole. The ball pitches and nips back in sharply off the surface. Nauman Ali gets caught on the crease as he looks to block it out. He misses and gets pinged in front. The finger goes up. This one seems to be adjacent but Pakistan haven't lost any reviews so decided to use one in hope. UltraEdge confirms that there's no bat involved and Ball Tracking comes up with three reds. Pakistan are in a spot of real bother now.
Starc pushes it even wider and Babar isn't going to play at that one. The ball goes along the ground towards the keeper.
FOUR! Nicely played! A wide yorker from Starc at well over 140 clicks. Babar Azam hangs deep and squeezes it past the slip cordon and into the third man fence.
Full, on the fifth stump line and at 144 kph. Babar jams it out towards covers.
Starc looks to attack the pads but spills it way down the leg side. Alex Carey does well to spring to his left and saves a certain boundary in the process as well.
Starc goes a bit wide of the crease and slants one in from outside off at 142 clicks. Babar Azam hangs back and has a poke at it but gets beaten past the outside edge.
Full and wide, slides on straight. Azam leaves it alone.
Full and on off. Ali does well to keep it out.
Pitched up and angled into off stump. Nauman Ali gets right behind the line of the ball to block.
Nauman Ali walks in next.

OUT! CASTLED! Pat Cummins picks up another wicket and Pakistan lose their sixth. Perfect length this time from the Aussie skipper. He knows Sajid Khan is looking to drive and hence bowls it a bit fuller, around 137 clicks but wide of off stump. Khan goes for the cover drive, playing away from his body and the ball just reverses in a bit. Khan gets an inside edge and the ball goes on to shatter the off stump. The hard work seems to be paying off for the visitors late in the day and they can now smell blood.
Full and straight, this is driven firmly towards the man at short mid on.
Fullish delivery, reversing into the off stump. Khan does well to keep it out.
The batter has just watchfully blocked this out.
Uses the angle of the bowler and flicks it to wide mid on for a single.

HUGE SHOUT FOR A CAUGHT BEHIND! To be honest, we also heard something. The umpire stays still and Australia don't have any reviews left. Fuller in length and outside off, Sajid Khan is lured into the drive but fails to connect. It goes behind to the keeper who collects and after a little pause, appeals. Everyone joins but nothing doing. The UltraEdge suggests that the noise was of the bat hitting the pitch. Sharp umpiring.
Back of a length, around off, Babar stands tall inside the crease and nudges it behind square leg for one.
Fuller in length and wide outside off, Babar drives off the front foot but finds the cover fielder.
Pitches it up and around off, clocking 140.3 clicks, Babar pushes it defensively to extra cover.
Outside off, on a good length, Babar makes a watchful leave.
Full and around off, angling in, it's defended back.
Cummins bends his back and delivers it short around off, Sajid leans back and then tries to play the ramp shot but misses. Pat sledges and Sajid smiles.
On a fuller length, around off and angling in, Khan defends it back to the bowler. Called a no ball for overstepping!
In the channel outside off, on a length, Sajid lets it be.
FOUR! That's a confidence booster! Cummins pitches it up and around off, Sajid Khan shows the full face of the bat and strokes it down the ground for a boundary at long on.
And again. Just outside off, on a length, straightening off the seam, Sajid gets across the stumps to defend but misses.
Serves it on a length and just outside off, Sajid Khan once again keeps his bat close to his body as it flies behind to the keeper.
As we head into the final hour of play on Day 3 and the Pakistani tail exposed, Pat Cummins brings himself back into the attack. He has picked up a couple of wickets for 51 runs so far in 21 overs.
Fuller in length and on middle, Khan flicks it behind square leg and opens his account with a single.
Nothing happens with this delivery. Starc lands it on a length and outside off, going straight on harmlessly. Sajid keeps his bat inside the line and allows it through.
Uses the angle of the bowler and keeps it out towards mid on.
Around off, angling in, defended by Sajid.
Sajid Khan is in at number 7 for Pakistan.

OUT! SOUND OF TIMBER! Starc is turning on the heat and doing the job for his team. It's certainly reversing and Starc becomes deadly when that happens. Mitch speeds in from 'round the wicket, he darts it on a length and around off at 138.5 kph. Mohammad Rizwan tries to cover the line and defend it but it straightens a hint to beat the bat and goes on to destroy the stumps. Mohammad Rizwan is left bamboozled. Australia have their tail up, Pakistan will feel the pressure as they still trail by 135 runs.
Starc goes full and serves it around leg, Babar clips it off his pads to deep backward square leg for a single.

Drinks break. 28 runs after the Tea break and it has been slow going from Pakistan. Australia have bowled accurately, drying out the runs and picked up the wicket of Fawad Alam as well a little while ago. Babar Azam is going strongly and the current stand between him and Rizwan is very important as this is the last recognized pair and the deficit is still 136 runs.
Lyon gives it a bit more air and allows it to turn in from around off. Mohammad Rizwan defends it out.
Fuller and on middle, pushed away towards mid on.
Tossed up, wide of off stump. Rizwan leans forward and uses his wrists to work it towards mid off.
A bit shorter this time, on middle. Rizwan works it towards mid-wicket.
Nicely flighted, around off and turning in. Rizwan stays watchful in defense.
This is pushed through around off. Rizwan goes deep in his crease to block it out.
A touch fuller and outside off. Azam strokes it towards covers.
Length again but there's width on offer this time. Babar Azam stands tall and times it nicely through the cover region for a brace.
A length ball, angled onto the hips. Mohammad Rizwan tickles it down to fine leg and gets off the mark with a single.
Starc angles it on the pads and Babar works it in front of square on the leg side for a single.
Full and wide, nicely driven but straight to the man at short cover.
On the pads, tucked away through the mid-wicket region for a couple of runs by Babar.
Shorter again, on off. Rizwan with a slight shuffle as he punches it firmly towards the mid-wicket region.
Pushed through on the off stump line. Rizwan blocks it from inside the crease.
Tossed up, quicker and fuller, on off stump. Mohammad Rizwan flicks it towards mid on.
A bit short and wide, Azam leans back and cuts it through backward point for a single.
On middle, this is defended off the front foot.
Turn and bounce! Shorter, on off and turning in a long way. Babar Azam looks to flick it off the back foot but gets hit on the pads. A stifled appeal from the bowler and nothing more.
Starc goes even quicker and curves it in from outside off at almost 145 clicks. Rizwan punches it out solidly towards short extra cover.
Fuller this time, on the sixth stump line. Rizwan pushes it out towards mid off.
Length again, at 141 clicks and angled in from wide of the crease. Rizwan hangs back and dabs it down towards point.
Mohammad Rizwan, the last recognized batter, is in next. Pakistan still trail by 143 runs.

OUT! Cleaned up! Mitchell Starc repays the faith his skipper has shown in him and gets the breakthrough. Starc angles it in from around the off stump line, on a nagging length, at 137 kph, that is full but not full enough. Fawad Alam looked unsettled for the entirety of his stay at the crease and goes on the back foot when he really should have come forward. The ball comes in with the angle, there could be some movement off the surface too, and goes through bat and pad, castling into off stump. Is this going to open the floodgates for the Aussies?
A length ball, hugging the tramline outside off. Fawad Alam throws his hands at it but fails to reach it.
'No, no, no, no, nooo' is the call from Fawad Alam. Starc slides it full and on the pads, it's clipped away to backward square leg and Alam denies the single.
Pat Cummins has decided to unleash Mitchell Starc (0/19 in 15 overs) again with things getting a bit monotonous.
This is spinning in from outside off. Babar Azam defends it off the front foot. End of a maiden over from Nathan Lyon - his 9th.
On off. Blocked out.
Shorter this time, on middle. Kept out off the back foot onto the leg side.
This is pushed through a bit quicker, on the fifth stump line. Babar Azam plays for the turn which isn't there and edges it down towards covers.
Around off and turning in, Azam strides out to defend.
This is floated up, on a length and outside off. Azam pushes it out on the off side.
Turning down the leg side, a bit on the shorter side, Fawad goes down to sweep but fails to connect.
Floated and around off, Fawad strides forward and defends it back from the inner half of his blade.
Very full and outside off, Fawad gets on the front foot and hits it down towards mid on.
Short and on middle, Babar goes back and pulls it to deep mid-wicket for a single.
Loopy and full around off, pushed off the front foot to covers.
Tossed up, around middle, flicked towards mid-wicket.
Serves it full and off, Fawad is forward again as he defends it off the inner half to mid-wicket.
Full and close to off, defended back.
Slower through the air, full and on middle from 'round the wicket, Fawad presses forward and defends it to point.
A touch short and outside off, cut through point for a single.
Presses forward to a full ball and defends it off the inner half to mid-wicket.
Well tossed up, full and outside off, Babar is forward in defense.
Loopy and a bit too full outside off, Fawad lunges and jams it down.
Tossed up, outside off and turning in, Fawad Alam strides forward and defends.
Short and around off, Babar moves back and smacks it to sweeper cover for a single.
Appeal for an lbw, not given! Australia don't have any reviews left, to waste. Flighted one, full and around leg, Babar steps down the track and tries to defend but gets an INSIDE EDGE on the pads.
Slower through the air, nice loop as it lands full around middle, Babar draws forward in defense.
Flatter and shorter around off, a leg spinner, Babar hangs back and pushes it towards the bowler.
Quicker one, full and around off, Fawad commits himself forward in defense and it goes off the outer edge to cover-point.
Loopy one, full and wide outside off, Babar reaches out and drills it to sweeper cover for one.
Very full and around off, defended down.
Slower through the air, full and close to off, Babar defends it back.
Around middle, skidding in, Fawad helps it towards mid-wicket and steals a quick run.
Drags his length short around off, Babar goes back and hits it to long on for a run.
Full and close to off, landing on the footmarks, Fawad Alam defends it solidly.
Flighted and outside off, left alone.

FIFTY! Picks the gap, picks a single and picks yet another fifty! Short and around off, Babar goes back and punches it to sweeper cover. Excellent knock from Azam and the crowd is loving his stay in the middle. Can he make a big one?
Tossed up and on middle, defended back.
Floated and full, around off, driven to mid off.
Swepson gets away with a poor delivery. Short and outside off, begging to be put away, Babar Azam slaps it straight to mid off.
On off, Alam gets right behind the line to kake the block.
A bit tossed up this time and pushed a bit wider. Fawad Alam has to reach out for it to block.
Flatter this time, close to the off stump line. Alam hops back and defends it out.
Flighted, on the fourth stump line. Alam reaches forward to defend.

A bit of a mix-up in the middle but no harm done. Slightly shorter and Alam forces it off his back foot. It beats the diving cover fielder but Usman Khawaja stops it with a dive at mid off. A single is on but Fawad turns it down eventually.

On a nagging length, around off and this is bowled at over 90 clicks. Fawad Alam gets rushed a bit and gets pushed onto the back foot. He is able to get his bat down in time though as he keeps it out to safety.
Flighted delivery, around middle. Azam stays solid in defense.
Swepson gives it a good rip this time and tosses it up on off. Babar Azam puts a big stride forward and defends it out.
Tossed up, full and on middle and leg. Babar drives it down towards mid on.
Around off, blocked out.

Shorter delivery on the off stump line. Babar Azam backs away a bit and runs it off the face of the blade past backward point. Mitchell Starc gives chase from the inner circle and keeps it down to a couple. Babar moves to 49 now.
Swepson starts from 'round the wicket to the left-hander and goes full, on off. Fawad Alam pushes it to the right of the mid on fielder and collects a single.
Mitchell Swepson (14-2-36-0) is back on.

Nicely bowled! On a shorter length, below 80 clicks and outside off. This one grips and turns back in sharply. Babar Azam though has enough time to go on the back foot and dab it down towards the point region.
Sliding onto the pads, this is worked 'round the corner for a single by Alam.
Loopy delivery, on middle, Fawad Alam gets a good stride forward to counter the turn and also the bounce.
Drifted into middle and leg now. Alam stays watchful in defense.
Flighted, full and close to the off stump. Alam plays it with the spin and keeps it out on the off side.
On a shorter length, on off. This one turns away but Alam has enough time to go onto the back foot and push it back towards the bowler.
Goes full and straight this time. Azam drives it towards mid on.
Just keeping the batter honest here Green. He bangs it in short and over the middle stump. Azam ducks under it and the ball doesn't bounce high enough.
This is slanted into middle. Babar defends it out solidly off the front foot.

Good-length delivery again, close to the off pole. Babar Azam stays in his crease and drives it on the up, in front of square on the off side. Mitchell Swepson runs around from the cover fence and keeps it down to a couple.
On a good length, over the off stump. Azam hangs back and keeps it out on the off side.
Green misses his mark this time and spills it way down leg. Alex Carey does well to dive low to his left and take it cleanly. He has certainly saved many boundaries today.
Quicker delivery, angled in from outside off. Alam gets pushed onto the back foot as he looks to cut but gets a bottom edge back onto the deck.
Loopy delivery, drifted into middle. Alam strides forward and blocks it out with soft hands.
Short and wide, keeping low this time. Alam cuts it off the back foot again towards the point region.
Flatter this time, close to the off pole. Fawad Alam rocks back and cuts it towards point.
Around off, Babar leans forward and pushes it towards covers for a single.
A bit of hesitation from the batters but they scamper through for the single. Nicely flighted, around off. Fawad Alam reaches out and nudges it past the fielder at short leg for a single.
Back of a length on off, Fawad moves across and nudges it down to fine leg for a single.
Bouncer around off, Fawad shuffles across a bit and then ducks.
Pitches it up and around off, Fawad gets forward and pushes it back. Green possibly fingertips it behind as the ball collides with the stumps. Babar is safely in though.
Hurls across a length ball outside off, Fawad covers his stumps and allows it through.
Slants in a length ball around off, from 'round the wicket, Fawad Alam closes the face of the bat and defends it to mid-wicket.
Angling down the leg side, a length ball, Babar eases it down to long leg and collects a single.
A touch short and on off, Fawad stays back in defense and does so off the inner half to short leg.
Floated and full, around off, Fawad presses forward and defends it from the splice of his bat. Some extra bounce there, something Fawad will have to be careful about.
Another delivery on the shorter side, around off, Babar punches it to sweeper cover for a single.
Short again from Lyon, around off, Fawad goes back to perhaps pull but ends up dragging it down the ground. The mid on fielder chases it down and they take three.
Loopy and full, around off and spinning away a bit, Fawad defends it off the front foot.
Short and outside off, Fawad goes back to cut but only manages to chop it down towards covers.
Nathan Lyon to resume his right-arm off-breaks from the opposite end.
Again it's full and around off, Babar defends.
Fuller and on middle, driven back and it went on to hit the stumps at the other end.

'CATCH IT!' It goes just wide of the bowler. Back of a length, around middle and leg, Babar tries to glance but closes the face of the bat early. It pops out off the leading edge and just evades the bowler as it goes down to mid off. Narrow escape.
Delivers it on a length around off, staying low, Babar defends it by taking his bottom hand off the handle.
Fuller and on off, Babar blocks it solidly to the off side.
Starts with a good-length delivery around off, Babar Azam stays on the back foot and helps it towards mid-wicket.

We are back for the final session of play on Day 3! 37 overs left in the day's play and with that said, Pat Cummins and his troops make their way out to the middle. Babar Azam and Fawad Alam are set to resume their innings after the interval. It's going to be Cameron Green to start off proceedings with the ball after the break. Let's go...
... Day 3, Session 3 ...

Australia lead by 164 runs and Pakistan still have 7 wickets in hand. But given the fact that they have gone in with the extra bowler, the only recognized batter left is Mohammad Rizwan. The final session of Day 3 becomes really vital given how things stand at the moment and one strong partnership will see Pakistan through onto Day 4 but a couple of wickets here and Australia will be right on top of things. The final session starts at 3.30 pm IST (10 am GMT). Do join us in a while.

Australia will breathe a lot easier after the afternoon session as they have been able to uproot both the set batters and know that if they get one more wicket early in the final session, they can have a go at the tail and maybe even clean up the hosts before the end of the day's play. That is a bit far-fetched but it can happen. Nathan Lyon bowled beautifully and got the vital breakthrough for the visitors which helped them get back in the contest. This was then followed up by a wonderful piece of catching off his own bowling by Pat Cummins later in the session. The likes of Starc, Green and Swepson need to pull up their socks a bit too and put pressure on Pakistan from all ends in order to end up with a decent lead.

Session summary: 25 overs, 68 runs and 2 wickets! There has been a bit of momentum shift in the second session but still, the hosts look fairly comfortable. After Abdullah Shafique got out, Babar Azam came in and looked to score runs and not get bogged down. He was able to do just that while Azhar Ali took up the anchor role. They looked good for a while but suddenly the ball went off the outside edge a bit more and eventually Ali got out to a stunning return catch from the opposition skipper. Fawad Alam has managed to stay with the skipper and see the side through to the Tea break.
Loopy delivery, full and around off, Fawad Alam stretches forward and defends it back. TEA ON DAY 3!
Tossed up, around off, Fawad goes back, follows the line of the delivery and defends it at the last moment. Not a good idea to read it from the pitch.
Drops it short and on off, Babar goes back and punches it to long on for one.
Strides forward to a full ball and defends it down on the surface.
Flighted and outside off, going straight on, Babar plays for the spin and gets beaten.
Flighted and full, outside off, defended to the off side.
Bouncer around middle and leg, Fawad Alam evades it safely.
On a length, around off and angling in, Fawad defends it from the back foot.
Stays on the back foot and steers it to deep point for a single.
Pitches it up and around off, Babar drives it back and Green makes the stop in his followthrough.
Gets behind the line of the delivery and pushes it defensively to mid off.
Fuller in length and outside off, Babar plays a mistimed drive back to the bowler.
Cameron Green (10-3-32-0) to have a short burst before the Tea break.
Full and on off, Fawad defends it on the leg side.
Living dangerously, Fawad. Tries to go back and cut this one but only manages an inside edge as the ball rolls on the leg side.
Flighted and off, defended off the front foot.

Nathan Lyon doesn't seem happy. He thinks that Fawad Alam is using the movement behind the sightscreen to delay things and Lyon wants him to get a move on. Alam comes forward and has a chat with the umpire and just wants time to concentrate.

Huge shout for an lbw, the finger has stayed down. Smith is unhappy with the decision. Lyon and Cummins have a chat and Australia take the DRS. Coming to the delivery, it's flighted and full around off, skidding in with the angle rather than spinning away. Fawad Alam is caught off guard as he picks the variation very late. Fawad tries to bring his bat down late to defend but it gets stuck a bit behind the flap of his back pad. He ends up getting struck on the back pad, the appeal is made but the umpire remains unmoved. The Ball Tracking finds the impact to be outside off. Australia have now no reviews left.
FOUR! Easy pickings! Short and wide from Lyon, outside off, Fawad Alam camps back and whacks it to the cover fence.
Leans forward to a full ball and defends it off the inner half to short leg.
Very full and on middle, staying low, Babar watches it very closely and brings his bat down in time to defend it towards mid on.
Around middle and leg, on a good length, Babar turns and flicks it to deep mid-wicket. Good timing and placement - two taken.
Fuller and around off, angling in and staying low at the same time, Babar defends it to mid-wicket.
Bumper around off, Babar Azam ducks at the last moment.
Short and around off, Babar plays a mistimed punch off the back foot to covers.
Fullish and on middle, Babar flicks but finds the fielder at short mid-wicket.
Tossed up and outside off, Fawad Alam keeps his bat inside the line as he makes a leave.

Edged but safe! Floated one, full and around off, Babar Azam tries to defend but it takes the outer edge and goes behind. Doesn't carry to first slip and sneaks past Smith's outstretched right hand. The batters take three by the time it's retrieved in the deep.

Gosh, that kept low! Fuller and around off, Babar Azam commits himself on the front foot in defense and keeps it near his front pad. The ball stays low, clips the bottom half and rolls wide of first slip.
Loopy and full, around off, Babar is forward as he defends it back to the bowler.
A touch short and on middle, from 'round the wicket, Fawad goes back and flicks it wide of mid on for a single.
Flatter and shorter on off, Babar goes back and eases it towards cover-point for a single.
Outside off, left alone. End of a successful over, a wicket maiden.
Cummins speeds in from 'round the wicket for the left-hander and delivers it on a length around off, Fawad gets behind the line and then defends.
Fawad Alam walks in to bat at number 5. He is taking his time to settle on the crease and has an issue with the sightscreen. The issue is fixed and we are good to continue.

OUT! SENSATIONAL RETURN CATCH! Captain Courageous has done it for his team. This man gives more than 100 per cent on the field, be it as a bowler or a fielder. Great athleticism shown by him to grab that. Patto is pumped up! Both the set batters have been removed in the afternoon session. Fuller in length, around off at 138.5 kph, Azhar Ali takes a tiny step forward and attempts to drive it down the ground. He fails to keep it down though and Cummins snaps it with both hands in his followthrough. Quite exceptional. Heartbreak not just for Azhar Ali but his son also who is watching from the stands. Pakistan trail by 177 runs.
Accuracy from Pat Cummins. He sticks to his line around off, delivering it on a length, Azhar defends. This one also stayed low.
Bowls it full and around off, Azhar stays low in his stance and works it away off his pads to wide mid on.
Keeps it on a length and around off, staying a fraction low, Azhar defends it near his front pad.
Floated this time, full and around off, Azhar forces it down to long on for a single.
Short and outside off, Babar goes back and punches it to sweeper cover for a single.
Flatter and outside off, Babar is on the back foot as he blocks it on the off side.
And again. Lyon sends it quicker through the air, full and outside off, Babar gets back to defend but it whizzes past the outside edge.
Beaten! Tossed up, outside off, Babar plays for the spin and gets beaten.
Flighted and full outside off, Azhar gets forward with a big stride and drops it with gentle hands to the right of the point fielder. They scamper across for a quick run.
Around the top of off. Azam hangs back and keeps it out towards the point region.

Shout for an lbw, the finger stays down! Not reviewed and rightly so. After being hit for a couple of boundaries, Pat Cummins bowls a peach of a delivery. This is bowled on a length, around off. The ball just hits a crack and nips back in sharply. Babar Azam gets completely caught on the crease and gets pinged on the pads. There is a stifled appeal from the visitors but they don't review it as it was certainly a bit too high and sliding down the leg side.
FOUR! Poor line again from Cummins and Babar picks up back-to-back boundaries. This is sliding down leg, Babar just tickles it fine and the ball races away to the fine leg fence.
FOUR! Babar Azam accepts the gift from Pat Cummins and picks up a boundary. Fired up, on the pads and this is flicked off the legs into the vacant backward square leg fence.
Length, angling into middle. Babar Azam defends it back onto the turf.
This one keeps low! Cummins angles it in from wide of the crease and at the pads. Azam does well to watch it all the way through and keeps it out on the leg side.
Pat Cummins (18-5-41-1) is back for another spell in the afternoon heat.
This is tossed up, outside off. Ali strides forward and defends it out.

Time and again Azhar Ali has looked for the hard sweep against Nathan Lyon but has failed to connect. This is pushed through a bit quicker and closer to the off stump. Ali gets down on one knee to sweep but the ball sneaks under his blade.
A bit of flight again, fuller and outside off. Ali squeezes it out towards point.
Nicely flighted, outside off. Ali strides out and pushes it onto the off side.
Fuller one, around the sixth stump line. This is blocked towards cover.
A bit shorter, turning in from outside off. Ali hangs back and pushes it off the back foot towards mid on. David Warner uses his boot to stop the ball rather than diving.

Early call for a run and they scamper through easily. Pitched up, on off. Ali presses forward and pushes it gently to the right of the mid off fielder. Khawaja gets across quickly and keeps it down to a single.
Full and wide, at 144.5 kph and this one slides across the batter. Azhar Ali makes the easiest of leaves.
Back of a length, around the body. Ali hops and dabs it down towards short mid-wicket.
Shorter in length, slanted across the right-hander. Azhar Ali bends his back and lets it through to the keeper. He leaves his bat dangling though.
Starc goes full and tries to angle it across the off stump. Ali opens up his arms a bit and firmly punches it towards the man at mid off.
Around the top of off at 143.1 kph. Azhar Ali hangs back and defends it out with soft hands towards short cover.
Short leg in place. There is a deep point as well.
Floated up, outside off. Ali leans in and pushes it towards covers for one more.
Full, on middle. This is tickled 'round the corner for a single.

EDGED AND FOUR! Nathan Lyon induces another edge but this one flies past first slip. Quicker and fuller, outside off and this one hits the rough. Babar Azam drives hard at it and gets a thick outside edge that goes to the left of Steven Smith at first slip and he has almost no time to react. The ball races away into the third man fence. Smudge is down on one knee, having a wry smile on his face. He knows that he is having a tough time in the slip cordon. By his standards, he is getting slow with his reflexes.
FOUR! Slapped away! Lyon drops it just s tad short and Babar Azam takes full advantage. Around off, Azam rocks back and cuts it through covers for a boundary.
A bit closer to off stump and quicker as well. This one spins back in sharply and Babar hops on the back foot to keep it out.
Flighted delivery, outside off. Babar gets a good stride forward to defend.

Drinks break. Another hour of engrossing action and Australia finally had some success through Nathan Lyon. Although the credit for that breakthrough should go more to Travis Head, who was standing at silly point, and heard the edge that the bowler and most of the close-in fielders failed to hear. The ball certainly has done more than the morning session. Nathan Lyon looked threatening whenever he pitched in good areas but Mitchell Swepson has been ordinary with his lengths. Australia have taken the second new ball and would be aiming to create more inroads. The lead for them is under 200 now. Nathan Lyon continues from the other end. The new nut will offer him a good grip.
Good parry away from Alex Carey. Starc goes fuller and quicker, trying to attack the pads but spills it way down leg again. Carey springs to his left and gets a glove on it.
Well bowled! Mitchell Starc goes for the effort ball and serves a bouncer over off stump. Azhar Ali ducks under it and the hard new ball carries nicely to Carey, who gloves it around his head.
This is spilled down the leg side, around 143 kph and Alex Carey does well to move to his left and pouch that one.
Pitched up, on off at 141.9 kph. The ball zips through and Ali plays a check-drive towards mid off.
Full and wide, at around 141 clicks. Starc looks to get it up there, inviting the drive and Ali does drive it towards the covers.
Movement in the air straightaway for Mitchell Starc! This is bowled very full, on middle and shapes back in nicely. Azam clips it towards the mid-wicket region for a single.
The second new ball is now available. Will Pat Cummins take it straightaway? Yes, he does! And it's going to be Mitchell Starc who will get the first bite at the red cherry.
Too full and on off, knocked down to long on for one.

Fuller and around off, Babar drives it through the line, through the legs of Travis Head at silly point, but finds the cover fielder. Steven Smith likes that line and length and encourages Lyon to bowl there more often.
That is defended solidly off the front foot to silly point.
Lunges to a full ball around off and defends.
7000 Test runs for Azhar Ali! He has been a great servant for Pakistan. Full and outside off, Azhar sweeps it past the leaping short leg fielder for a single.
A touch uppish. Fuller and around off, turning in with some extra bounce, Ali flicks it to the right of mid-wicket and the fielder makes a fine diving stop.
Fullish and around leg, defended towards short mid-wicket.
Quicker and shorter on off, Ali goes back and slaps it to sweeper cover for one.
Flatter and around leg, helped to backward square leg.
Loopy and around leg, it's defended off the front foot.
Flighted and on leg, flicked to mid-wicket.
Floated and on off, defended with the spin to the off side.
Flighted and full outside off, Babar gets forward and across in defense.
Full and on off, that is defended solidly off the front foot.

SIX! Dispatched! Loopy and full, landing close to off, Babar Azam wears his skates to come down the track and seeing that the silly point fielder jumps for cover. He is not in danger though as Babar goes downtown and sends it flying over long on for a maximum.
Gets on the front foot and defends it to mid-wicket.
Slightly short and on off, Ali gets back and punches it towards mid-wicket. The fielder there is lazy in getting down and allows it through to long on. A single is taken.
Puts a flighted ball on a fuller length around off, Azhar presses forward and defends.
This length won't trouble the batter. Mitchell Swepson is again on the shorter side, around off, Babar forces it off the back foot to covers.
A leg spinner on the shorter side around middle, Babar goes back and punches it to mid on.
Nice flight on this delivery but the length is a little too full, around middle, Azhar Ali drives it to mid off and takes a quick run.
Fuller in length and around leg, it's turned towards the square leg umpire for a single.
Drags his length short and delivers it outside off, Babar Azam cuts but finds the point fielder.
Very full in length and around leg, Babar defends it towards mid on.
Pat Cummins takes a break after that short burst and it's now going to be spin from both ends. Mitchell Swepson (12-2-33-0) is back on.
Goes on the back foot and eases a short ball down to long on for a single.
Presses forward to a full ball and defends it back to the bowler.

FOUR! Put away! Not sure whether that slipped away from Lyon's hand or it was intentional. A long hop on middle, Babar Azam goes back and pulls it past short leg for a boundary. Marnus Labuschagne was there in the firing line and turns full 360 to protect himself.
Flighted again, full and outside off, Babar takes a big stride forward as he defends it back.
Loopy and full, drifting in around off, Babar Azam gets on the front foot in defense.
Flatter and on off, Azhar Ali goes back and punches it down to long on for a run.
A length ball, angled into off. This one doesn't rise up much either and Azam watches it all the way through to keep it out.
Full and straight, Babar Azam with a firm push back towards the bowler who does well to get a hand on it.
This one reverses back into the right-hander. It is full and on middle, Azam flicks it towards mid-wicket.
Rameez Raja, the chairman of PCB, is walking around the stadium with a big entourage. It's Pakistan Day and he is seen distributing the Pakistan flag.

Pat Cummins certainly won't mind that shot from Babar Azam. On a driving length, outside off and shaping away a bit. Azam plays away from the body and gets it through cover-point for a couple of runs.
Back of a length, around the fourth stump line. Azam hangs back and looks to punch it through covers but gets it off the toe end of the bat.
On a good length, over off. Babar Azam gets squared up a bit but manages to block it out on the off side.
Tossed up, wide of the off pole and this one keeps a tad low. Azhar Ali lunges forward and manages to get to the pitch of the ball as he defends it to silly point.
A bit flatter from Lyon, close to the off stump line. Ali goes on the back foot and keeps it out on the off side.
Around off, Ali reaches out and flicks it onto the leg side.
Flighted, outside off. Ali gets a big stride forward and pushes it past silly point.
Azhar Ali trying to counterattack. This is pushed fuller and wider, turning in sharply. Ali looks to fetch it and broom it away but misses. Ali looking to play a risky game here.
On off and turning in, Ali lunges forward and pushes it towards silly mid on.
Cummins seems all pumped up now! Goes full again but angles this one in, attacking the pads. Babar Azam just about manages to get his bat down in time. End of a probing over from Cummins.
Nicely bowled! A bit wider again, fuller and just shaping away ever so slightly. Babar looks to play at it but watchfully lets it through to the keeper.

Length this time, on the fifth stump line and shaping away a bit. Babar Azam stays rooted in his crease and pushes it towards cover away from the body. They look for the single but decide against it in the end.
A bit too straight from Pat Cummins and Azhar Ali is able to just flick it off his legs to deep square leg for a single.
Full and straight, angling into middle and leg. Ali clips it towards mid-wicket.

On the bounce to Steven Smith at first slip! Cummins bowls it a tad fuller, in that channel around off. Azhar Ali has a push at it but there's no feet movement. The ball goes off the outside edge and luckily for Ali, it falls well short of first slip.
Pat Cummins is back into the attack.

That's a gem to beat the bat! Tossed up, landing a touch short outside off and goes straight on, Babar Azam is on the back foot, trying to defend with the spin and gets beaten on the outside edge. Top over, a wicket maiden!
Flighted and around off, defended towards silly point.
Leans forward to a full ball and defends it to the leg side.
Oohhh...a bit aerial, that! Full and flighted on off, Babar gets forward to defend it with hard hands. It bobbles up and goes just wide of the outstretched right hand of Travis Head at silly point.
Babar Azam walks in next. The crowd has gone vocal. Pakistan trail by 221 runs.

OUT! There is a spike on the UltraEdge and finally, Australia have a breakthrough that they so desperately needed. Lyon tosses it up nicely outside off and on a nagging length. Abdullah Shafique prods forward and has a push at it but seems to be beaten past the outside edge as this one doesn't turn. There is not much appeal from Alex Carey behind the stumps but Travis Head at silly point is very much interested as he turns and appeals vociferously. Australia have just one review left and eventually, Pat Cummins decides to take the chance. UltraEdge shows that there is a clear spike as the ball goes past the bottom part of the bat and the on-field decision will be reversed. Sharp take from Carey but strangely he had no idea about the outside edge. Shafique departs after a top knock. Full marks to Travis Head there as he was the only one convinced, neither the bowler nor the keeper appealed much.
Commentary.Howout: c Alex Carey b Nathan Lyon

Commentary.Commentary: Lyon slows it up and bowls it on a length outside off. He gets sharp turn and bounce off the footmarks. Shafique watches it all the way through and nudges it down past short leg.
On middle this time, Ali flicks it straight to the man at short mid-wicket. Maiden!
Full and wide, there's movement in the air. Ali pushes it towards covers.

The visitors seem a bit interested but it's definitely off the arm guard and Steven Smith signals the same later on. Mitchell Starc bends his back and bangs it in short around leg. The ball reverses a bit again and Azhar Ali looks to sway away from the line of the ball. He takes his eyes off the ball and it keeps low. Goes off the arm guard towards first slip where Smith dives forward to pouch it.
This is pitched up on off. Ali presses forward to defend it out.

Nicely bowled and Starc does get a little bit of reverse this time. Goes full, on middle and at 141.9 kph. The ball tails away from the batter at the last moment but Azhar Ali does well to jam it out.
A length ball, around the top of off and at 141 clicks. Ali hangs back in his crease and nudges it down towards covers.

FOUR! Fine sweep shot! Flighted and full, around middle, Abdullah Shafique goes down on one knee and sweeps it crisply through square leg for a boundary. The 150-run stand comes up between Azhar Ali and Abdullah.
Goes on the back foot and punches it to covers.
Fuller and on off, flicked to mid-wicket.
Again it's short and around off, Abdullah Shafique goes back to cut but ends up chopping down to covers.
A touch short and on off, Abdullah Shafique goes back and punches but finds the fielder at covers.
Loopy and full around off, Shafique walks forward and pushes it back to the bowler.
Fuller in length and outside off, leaving the batter with the angle, Ali just stands there and watches it go to the keeper.
Streaky! Full in length and close to off, nipping away, Abdullah Shafique tries to defend off the front foot but it takes the outer edge and speeds through point for a single.
Angling away from the batter, on a length, Abdullah Shafique shoulders arms.
Back of a length, again down the leg side, this time Abdullah Shafique allows it through.
Slips a length ball down the leg side, the batter fails to make any use of it. A good take by Alex Carey.
Starc runs in from over the wicket and pitches it up around off, Abdullah Shafique gets on the front foot and defends it back to the bowler. There was some movement in the air for Mitch!

Mitchell Starc to bowl from the opposite end. He has bowled 11 overs so far, giving away 16 runs. Also, legendary Pakistani bowler, Waqar Younis was inducted into the PCB Hall of Fame during the Lunch break at his home ground and that too on Pakistan Day. A proud moment for him and his family.
Flighted and on off, Ali goes back and defends it down safely.
A touch short and on off, it's punched down to long on for a single.
Around off, forced down to long on for a single.
Gets on the font foot and defends it down.
FOUR! Good intent shown by the batter! Loopy and full around off, Azhar Ali goes down on one knee and slog-sweeps it along the ground through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Full delivery, landing on the rough outside off, the batter flicks on the leg side but finds short mid-wicket.

We are back for the post-Lunch session on Day 3! The umpires and the Australian players are already out in the middle. The two batters at the crease for Pakistan, Abdullah Shafique and Azhar Ali resume their stay after the interval. It's going to be spin to start proceedings as Nathan Lyon has the ball in hand.
... Day 3, Session 2 ...

We are almost halfway through the third and final Test match and no one can predict as to which side is going to win the match and the series as well. We don't even know if there's going to be a winner at all. Another intriguing session of Test cricket has flown by and there's more to come. The post-Lunch session begins at 1.10 pm IST (7.40 am GMT). Do join us shortly.

Australia will feel a bit disheartened with that session as they failed to get any breakthrough but Pat Cummins started off well and then ended well too. For the most part of the session, the Aussie spinners didn't look to be causing much trouble to the Pakistani batters but with half an hour or so remaining, Nathan Lyon did start to make inroads and got the ball to talk a bit and then in the final over of the session, Mitchell Swepson created a catching opportunity. These are encouraging signs for the spinners. Both of them will look to come back fresh after the break and make full use of the ever-drying surface by picking up a few wickets.

Session summary: 28 overs, 69 runs, 0 wickets! Pakistan still trail by 232 runs but didn't lose a single wicket in the opening session of Day 3. Abdullah Shafique and Azhar Ali have remained rock solid and have frustrated the opposition bowlers. Both of them have set up a brilliant platform from where they can go on and get to the three-figure mark individually and cut down the lead even further. With in-form batters like Babar Azam and Mohammad Rizwan still to come, the hosts look well on course to playing out the entirety of Day 3 unless there's an uncanny collapse somewhere in between.
Flatter and on middle, Abdullah Shafique goes back and tucks it towards mid-wicket. That will be LUNCH ON DAY 3!
Floated and just around off, Abdullah Shafique covers his stumps and offers no shot.
Fuller and around off, defended off the inner edge to square leg.

EDGED BUT SAFE! Steven Smith gets fingertips on it. Tossed up, around off and a bit on the shorter side. Azhar Ali hangs back and tries to play at it late. But the ball spins away at the point of contact and takes the outside edge. Steven Smith, at first slip, initially reacts to his right but then realizes that it's speeding through his left side. He sticks his left hand out but the ball only brushes his fingers and runs down towards third man. The batters cross. A chance for Australia at the stroke of Lunch goes begging. Smudge has had a torrid time in the slips in this series.
Loopy and around leg, defended off the front foot.

FOUR! Poor start from Swepson! He drags his length short and serves it around off, Azhar goes back and whips it through the gap at mid on. Usman Khawaja gives the chase, puts in a dive as if diving in a swimming pool but fails to pull it back.
Mitchell Swepson to bowl the final over before Lunch.
Quicker and fuller around leg, defended to short leg.
Flighted delivery, around leg from 'round the wicket, Abdullah Shafique helps it to backward square leg.
Short in length and around off, too close to cut, Abdullah Shafique chops it down towards cover-point.
Leans forward to a full ball and offers a straight bat in defense.
A touch flatter and on middle, Abdullah Shafique works it away off his pads but finds backward square leg.
Tossed up, full and on off, defended to short leg.
Identical to the last delivery, Ali leans across a bit and again clips it to short mid-wicket.
Full and on middle, flicked to short mid-wicket.
Around off, on a shortish length, Ali is a bit squared up but does well to guide it down to third man for a couple of runs.
Back of a length, around off and jumping up a shade at 139.5 clicks, Ali is on his toes as he defends it down safely.
Fuller and on off, driven down the ground but straight to mid on.
Excellent stop by Carey. Drifting down the leg side, on a length, Ali fails to flick and Alex Carey makes a diving stop to his left.
A bit short on this occasion, around off, Abdullah Shafique goes back, takes care of the spin and punches it in the gap at covers for a couple of runs.
Presses forward to a full ball and defends it back.
Flatter this time, short and on off, blocked from the back foot by Abdullah Shafique.
Full and flighted outside off, Abdullah Shafique leans forward and across as he works it gently to short mid-wicket.
Loopy and full on off, defended back.
Flighted off spinner, landing full around off, Abdullah Shafique defends it from the inside edge to backward square leg.
Close to off and on a length, Azhar tries to play late and guide it down to third man. But Green intervenes with a dive from second slip and parries it to point.
Angling in from around off, Azhar defends it from the crease to short mid-wicket.
Fuller and on off, defended back to the bowler.
Full in length around off, shaping back in at 136.7 clicks, once again Azhar is opened up in defense and keeps it out from the outer half of his willow to covers.
A tempter, it's served on a driving length outside off, Azhar doesn't fall for it and allows it through to the keeper.
Darts in a length ball around off, straightening a touch after landing at 134.7 clicks, Azhar Ali is squared up in defense as he defends it towards point.
Loopy and full, outside off, Abdullah Shafique walks down the track and defends it from the inner half of his blade to short mid-wicket.
Flatter and shorter, around off and turning in, Abdullah Shafique goes on the back foot and defends it on the leg side.
Uses his feet to come down the track and pushes a full ball back to the bowler.
Lunges to a full ball landing around off and dead-bats it on the surface.
A bit short and on off, Ali goes back and punches it to the left of the cover fielder for a quick run.
Flighted and full, landing around off, it's defended off the front foot to cover-point.
In the region outside off, on a driving length, Abdullah Shafique covers the stumps and allows it through.
On a shortish length and around off, Abdullah Shafique goes on the back foot and taps it down to short cover.
Good line again, full and close to off, Abdullah Shafique is solidly behind the line as he blocks it to covers.
Fuller and on off, defended down towards mid on.
Lands it on a length and around off, Shafique defends it to the off side.
On a length and in the channel outside off, Abdullah Shafique shoulders arms.

EDGED AND FOUR! Good line from Cummins but it goes for a boundary. Full in length and around off, holding its line, Abdullah Shafique pushes inside the line and gets a soft outside edge. It rolls wide of second slip and races away. Called a no ball for overstepping.
Pat Cummins (13-4-31-1) to have another burst before Lunch.
Lyon zips this one through, around off. Azhar Ali goes back in his crease and manages to keep it out.
Quicker again, around off. Azhar Ali goes back and across to make the block.
A bit closer to the off stump line now. Ali gets a big stride forward and keeps it out.
Quicker and flatter, turning in from outside off. Ali hangs back and nudges it out.
This is a bit wider as well. Ali defends it out on the off side this time.

Azhar Ali trying to be a bit funky now. This is pushed well outside off and there is a change in the field as silly point is kept in place and the boundary square on the leg side is left vacant. Ali looks to fetch the wider delivery and sweep it across but is comprehensively beaten.
On middle, Shafique strides out to defend.
Swepson looks to replicate the delivery from a couple of balls earlier as he floats it up around the pads again. This is a bit fuller and Shafique is able to flick it through mid-wicket for a brace.
This is a bit quicker and flatter, around off. Blocked.
Floated up, full and on off. Shafique blocks it out.

Ripper of a delivery from Mitchell Swepson! Tosses this one up, around the leg stump line and gives it a lot more air. The ball grips and turns away sharply. Abdullah Shafique is left bamboozled as the ball whizzes past the outside edge.
Flatter delivery, on middle and leg. Shafique goes deep in his crease to force it through mid-wicket but can't find the gap.
Full and wide, defended out on the off side.

Oooh, a bit of bounce! This is quicker at 95.1 kph and lands on a length around off. Azhar Ali looks to get behind the line of the ball to block but the ball pops up off the surface and Ali gets hit on the gloves, but manages to keep it down.
This is floated up full and outside off. Abdullah Shafique has a slight shuffle and he pushes it down to long on for a single.
Slow spin back into the batter from outside off, Abdullah Shafique defends it from the back foot.
Loopy and full around off, it's defended back off the front foot.
Short in length and outside off, Abdullah Shafique goes on the back foot and cuts it through point for a couple of runs.

Appeal for a run out! The umpires went upstairs pretty late just to double-check as Azhar Ali lost control of his bat. Tossed up, on off. This is pushed towards covers for a quick single. The throw comes in towards the keeper's end and Ali is well in but for a split second, after he lost his bat, his foot was off the ground. The bails are whipped off but the replay confirms that Ali is fine. To be honest, it's always a poor technique to plonk your bat inside the crease rather than sliding it in. Ali plonks it down, his bat got stuck a bit and then his left knee knocked down the blade. He though was safely in by then.
Fuller and on the pads, flicked away towards square leg. Shafique wants the single but is sent back by his partner.
Loopy delivery, on off. Shafique blocks it out.
Early call of 'no' from Shafique. Around leg, this is tucked away 'round the corner towards backward square leg.
Tossed up this time, on the pads. Ali works it nicely through mid-wicket and rotates the strike.
Quicker and flatter, attacking the stumps. Ali goes deep in his crease to keep this one out.
