Commentary.Commentary: Forces a length ball through the line but picks out the cover fielder.
Delivers it on a good length, close to off, Smith stands back inside the crease and defends it towards mid off.
Tap and run! A touch short and around off, Usman taps it down to the right of the cover fielder and steals a run.
Lands it on a good length and outside off, Usman Khawaja punches it from the back foot to covers.
Quicker, flatter and fuller, around off, Khawaja stays back and flicks it through square leg for a single.
Slower through the air, short and outside leg, Smith moves back and works it towards backward square leg for a run.
A conventional sweep from Usman as he fetches a full ball from outside off. He sends it to deep mid-wicket and collects a single.
Flatter and around leg, nudged behind square leg for one.
DROPPED! Azhar Ali drops a dolly! Tossed up, full and around leg, Smith brings out the reverse hit but gets a big top edge. It flies to long off where Ali spills the chance. Two taken.
Loopy and around leg, targeting the rough, Smith tries to paddle sweep but misses.
Nauman Ali to continue with his left-arm off-breaks from the opposite end.
Back of a length, around off and nipping back in, Khawaja tries to work it around but misses. Takes a blow on his thigh pad.
Pitches it up and around off, Smudge drives it to covers where the fielder dives and makes a half-stop. The ball rolls to mid off and they cross.
Lands it on a length and close to off, Smith stands across inside the crease and pushes it away to covers.
A touch short and outside off, Usman forces it from the back foot through point for a single.

FOUR BYES! Naseem is not able to control the movement at the moment. Sprays another one down the leg side, this time to a left-hander. Khawaja fails to flick and Rizwan too fails to collect with a dive to his right. Bonus runs for Australia. The lead is now 330.
Little bit of reverse again but the line is down the leg side. Smith tries to flick but misses. It takes his pads and goes behind. Rizwan dives to make a partial stop and they cross for a leg bye.

We are back for the final session on Day 4 and boy, it's a big one given the context of the match and the series as well. So, Australia lead by 325 runs and will look to add a few quick runs after the Tea break and set a target for their opponents. Steven Smith and Usman Khawaja resume their innings after the interval and the Pakistani players spread out on the field. Naseem Shah to start off with the ball after the break. He's bowled 10 overs so far giving away just 19 runs but hasn't had any success so far in this innings.
... DAY 4, SESSION 3 ...

105 runs in the second session at a run rate just above 4! Job well done by the touring team. They have extended their dominance in this Test match by going ahead by 325 runs. Usman Khawaja and Marnus Labuschagne batted for the majority of the afternoon session and dealt with the threat of reverse swing judiciously. The star of the second segment has to be Usman Khawaja, who completed his century and played a big role in keeping the Pakistan bowlers at bay. The hosts bowled well, mainly Shaheen Afridi and Naseem Shah, but they weren't consistent enough. Pakistan are firmly pushed on the back foot and will be waiting for the declaration now. What's the figure in the mind of Pat Cummins? 350 or more? We will find out shortly. Do join us at 3.30 pm IST (10 am GMT) for the final session.
Around off, Khawaja blocks it out again and that will be Tea on Day 4!
Floated up, outside off. Khawaja strides out to defend.

Misfield and Usman Khawaja scampers back for two. It is yet another HUNDRED on this tour for the southpaw and he is absolutely pumped up. Flatter delivery, around off. Khawaja cuts it towards cover-point and looks for two straightaway. They won't get it though... hang on, the fielder fumbles and they do get back for the second. Khawaja takes off his helmet and takes in the applause from the crowd and his teammates on the balcony. What a series this has been for him!
Flatter again, around off. Dabbed down on the off side.
Quicker one, on a length and outside off. This one hits the rough and turns back in sharply. Khawaja is taken by surprise and gets it on the arm.
Flatter delivery, outside off. Khawaja gets behind the line of the ball to make the block.
Full and sliding down leg, Khawaja flicks it towards fine leg and picks up a single. He moves on to 98 now.
Length again, stroked away through the cover region for one more.
Good-length, around the fourth stump line and cutting back into the batter, Steven Smith stays deep in his crease and tucks it towards square leg.
On middle, Smith blocks it out.

Risky single and Steven Smith has to put in the desperate dive. Fuller in length, on off. Usman Khawaja punches it towards covers and sets off for a single. Smith has to scamper through but the fielder misses the direct hot at the batter's end.
Length again, around the top of off. Khawaja looks to cover drive on the up but mistimes it towards the cover region.
Shorter this time, on the pads. Khawaja goes on the back foot and flicks it past square leg for one more.
On off, Khawaja walks towards the ball and clips it to mid-wicket. Steven Smith shouts 'no' nice and early to deny the run.
Around the leg stump, Smith works it behind square on the leg side and picks up a single.
On off, flicked away towards mid-wicket for a single.
Ali sees Smith stepping out and fires it in full and at the toes. Smith makes room and forces it towards mid off for a quick single.
Tossed up, around off. Khawaja slogs it with the spin towards deep mid-wicket for a single.
On a good length, close to the off stump and reversing in. Smith nudges it down towards point.
Full again, close to the off stump. Smith jams it out on the off side.

FOUR! Milestone for Steven Smith as he becomes the quickest batter to reach the 8000-run mark in Test cricket, in 151 innings, surpassing Kumar Sangakkara who achieved this feat in 152 innings. This is served on a driving length, outside off. Smith leans in and creams it through extra cover for a boundary, beating the diving attempt from Sajid Khan. A modern-day great, Smudge! Of late he has been short of big runs but his form has remained intact.
A length ball, angling into the top of off. Smith keeps it out.
Fullish delivery, around off. Khawaja walks towards the ball and steers it off the toe end of the bat towards deep backward point for a single.
Very full and very wide, just reversing away a bit. Usman Khawaja looks to drive away from the body but doesn't reach the ball.

There is some issue with the ball. The umpires are getting it changed. The box of balls that has come out doesn't have the desired option and the reserve umpire runs back to get more options. Ready to roll again...
Full and straight, flicked through mid-wicket for a single.
Close but not close enough. On a length, around off and turning in. Usman Khawaja attempts the reverse sweep again but doesn't connect. The ball bounces over the leg stump.
Tossed up on middle. Khawaja pushes it towards silly mid on.
This is floated up way down the leg side. Smith watches it all the way through and nudges it to the left of Fawad Alam at short fine leg for a run.
Spinning into off, worked through mid on for an easy single.
On a shorter length, turning in from outside off. Khawaja rocks back and punches it towards covers.
Full again, around off. This is driven through extra cover for a brace by Steven Smith.
Well bowled! Slightly fuller, reversing back into middle and leg. Smith gets his front pad across and makes the block.
Hasan Ali goes full and gets it to reverse back into off stump. Steven Smith stays deep in his crease and keeps it out.
A length ball, at 140.1 kph and over middle. Khawaja makes a bit of room by moving on the leg side and taps it towards cover-point for a quick single.
Fullish delivery, angled into middle and just straightening a bit. Khawaja keeps it out on the leg side.
Full and close to the off stump line. This is punched from inside the crease towards short cover.
Floated up at the pads, this is nudged away through square leg for a single.
The body language of the Aussie batters indicates that they want to score maximum runs from the overs left in this session. We can smell a declaration. Perhaps 350 is the figure.
Another attempted reverse sweep. On a shorter length, turning in from outside off. Khawaja strides out and looks to reverse it but misses and gets hit high on the pads.
This is fuller and at the toes. Smith steps out, makes a bit of room and pushes it down to long off for a single.
Well, that was ambitious! Very slow through the air and a bit shorter down the leg side. Steven Smith looks to reverse sweep it but he isn't reaching that one.
On the pads, flicked away through mid-wicket for one more.
The lead goes past 300 now. Floated up, full and around off. Usman Khawaja reverse-bats it fine towards the third man fence. Shaheen Afridi runs around and keeps it down to a brace.
Angled onto the pads, worked away off the legs for a run. The lead moves on to 299 runs.
FOUR! Usman Khawaja is on the march here. Full and wide, this is carved away behind square on the off side for the third boundary in the over.
FOUR! It's too straight this time from Hasan Ali and it's an easy put away for Khawaja. Sliding onto the pads, clipped away to the mid-wicket fence.
This is angled into middle. Khawaja pushes it towards mid on.
FOUR! The boundaries just keep on coming. Usman Khawaja with a lovely shot. Hasan Ali provides a bit of width and Khawaja just steers it behind point for a boundary.
Pitched up on off. Khawaja pushes it towards mid off.
This is fired in flatter and on middle. Khawaja goes on the back foot and wrists it through square leg for one more. 6 runs and a wicket off Nauman Ali's fourth over.
Down the leg side, Steven Smith gets inside the line of the ball and paddles it fine towards fine leg and gets off the mark with a single.
Switches back to 'round the wicket for the new batter. This is fired in full and on off. Smith blocks it out.
Steven Smith walks in next at number 4.

OUT! CAUGHT! The trap was set and Marnus Labuschagne falls into it perfectly! Nauman Ali is coming from over the wicket, trying to make use of the rough. Ali bowls it a bit quicker and fuller, around the leg stump line. Labuschagne gets down on one knee and has a bit of a swat at it. Labuschagne doesn't time it well enough and the ball flies down off the top edge towards the man stationed at the mid-wicket fence. Sajid Khan takes a simple catch and Nauman Ali is elated. Australia lead by 284 runs.
Commentary.Howout: c Sajid Khan b Nauman Ali

Commentary.Commentary: Ali tries to stem the flow of runs and opts for the negative line. This is way down the leg side and Labuschagne just pads it away.
Extended chat between the bowler and Babar Azam. Nauman Ali seems to be demanding a particular field, Babar though is seen shaking his head. Not sure whether there was any change in the field.

FOUR! Nauman Ali sees Marnus Labuschagne advancing and tries to fire it in at the toes. Labuschagne drills it on the full and through mid on for a boundary. Australia inching closer to that elusive 300-run lead.
Around the top of off. Khawaja hops back and dabs it down towards backward point.
This is pitched up around off. Usman Khawaja drives on the up but the fielder at covers makes a good half stop. The other fielder from extra cover runs after it and keeps it down to a couple.
On off, pushed onto the off side.

Geez, that one kept low! Naseem Shah gets this one to tail in a long way from around off and the ball skids through the surface. Usman Khawaja just about manages to get his bat down in time. This is really good bowling but the batting is upto the mark as well.
Fullish delivery, sliding into middle and leg. Khawaja flicks it towards mid on.
Pitched up on off at 140.5 kph. Khawaja hangs back to defend.

FOUR! Marnus Labuschagne looking to up the ante now. Tossed up, on middle. Labuschagne gets down on one knee and slogs it against the turn. He gets a top edge over the mid-wicket region and the ball trickles away into the fence.
Around middle and leg, Labuschagne gets inside the line of the ball and paddles it past the keeper for a couple of runs.
Lovely flight on that occasion! On middle and leg, Marnus Labuschagne stretches out to defend but the ball holds a bit in the pitch and goes off the leading edge towards the cover region.
Ali drags back the length a bit and bowls it at the stumps. Khawaja walks towards the ball and tucks it away to deep square leg for a run.
This is a bit quicker and fired in outside off. Usman Khawaja looks for the reverse sweep but doesn't connect.
Flighted ball, around off. Khawaja uses his feet and works it towards mid on.
Sajid Khan is given a rest and Nauman Ali is brought back into the attack.
Full and on middle again, worked through mid-wicket by Khawaja for a single.
Full and on middle and leg, this is flicked through the mid-wicket region for a couple of runs. The 50 partnership is up between these two.

Lovely bowling! Naseem Shah is really getting it to reverse now. On a nagging length, angling in from outside off but this one moves away quite a fair bit. Usman Khawaja hangs back and has a poke at it. He gets beaten past the outside edge and Shah is a bit interested but no one else is.
On a length, angled in from outside off. This one goes away a fraction and keeps low too. Khawaja gets beaten past the outside edge and Rizwan does well to get his body behind the double bounce.
Around the top of off, punched off the front foot towards the cover region for a quick single. Good running.
A length ball around off. This one tails back in and Labuschagne does well to keep it out on the leg side.

Drinks! It's been a pretty relaxed first hour of the second session for the Australian batters. Usman Khawaja has been able to just knock it around and get the scoreboard ticking. Marnus Labuschagne on the other hand has looked to play a few shots. The Pakistan bowlers are having to toil and even though Shaheen Afridi and Naseem Shah are getting it to reverse, the opposition batters don't seem to be bothered that much. Australia's lead is worth 267 runs and they will look to add at least 50 odd runs to that before the Tea break. Nauman Ali dropped Labuschagne early in his innings and he's looking to make them pay.
Nicely tossed up, on off. Usman Khawaja defends it under his eye line.
On off, blocked.
Flatter delivery, played towards point for a single.
Labuschagne shimmies down the wicket yet again and Sajid bowls it full and wide. Labuschagne manages to reach it and plays it towards mid off.
Around off, worked away through mid on for an easy single.
Full and wide, Labuschagne plays the reverse sweep again. The ball goes off the gloves and Babar misfields at first slip. He accidentally boots it behind and they get a single.
On a length, angled in from well outside off. Khawaja blocks it out from his crease.
Now the away movement. Good-length, slanted into off but moves away. Labuschagne hangs back and dabs it down towards backward point for a run.
Naseem tails this one back in from a fullish length, outside off and at 143.9 kph. Labuschagne blocks it out on the off side.
Close to 140 kph and this one tails back in sharply into middle and leg. Labuschagne stays watchful in defense and keeps it out.
A touch fuller, tailing back in from around off. Labuschagne defends it out on the leg side.
A length ball, around off and this one reverses back into the batter. Labuschagne hangs deep and keeps it out on the off side.
Good use of the feet again by Marnus. Tossed up, on middle. Marnus steps down the track and eases it down to long on for one.
Flatter delivery, close to the off pole. Labuschagne hangs back and just opens the face of the bat and plays it towards backward point.
Nicely flighted, full and well outside off. Labuschagne looks to sweep but drags it towards the mid-wicket region.
Around off and turning in. Blocked.
Floated up, outside off. Labuschagne reaches out looking to reverse paddle but toe-ends it to first slip.
FOUR! Thumped! Tossed up, around off. Marnus Labuschagne skips down the track and hits through the line, over the bowler's head and over mid off, for a boundary.
Pitched up, around off. Khawaja with a stylish drive on the up towards short cover.
This is slanted into middle. Khawaja gets pushed onto the back foot but keeps it out.
Naseem tries to reverse it back in a long way from outside off but doesn't get enough movement. Khawaja makes an easy leave.
Length again, on off. Khawaja strides out and defends it to short cover.
Just a touch fuller, angled into off stump. Usman Khawaja blocks it out solidly off the front foot.
Hitting the top of off, at 141 clicks. Khawaja defends it out.
Excellent running yet again from these two! Down the leg side, tickled away to short fine leg for a quick single.
Floated up, on the pads. Usman Khawaja clips it through mid-wicket and picks up a couple of runs.

Bye! Through everyone! Tossed up, full and outside off. Labuschagne looks to fetch it and sweep it but gets completely beaten. The ball goes through the legs of Mohammad Rizwan behind the stumps and they pick up a bye.
On middle, Khawaja uses his feet and works it towards the mid-wicket region for a single.

FOUR! Top shot from Usman Khawaja. A tad shorter, close to the off pole. Khawaja rocks onto the back foot and pushes it out through cover-point. Naseem Shah gives chase and slides in to cut it off but his foot is touching the rope at the same time. Boundary signalled after getting the confirmation from upstairs. The lead crosses 250 now!
Good running! Flighted, on off and turning in. Labuschagne looks to play it with the spin towards mid-wicket but gets it off the inside edge towards short fine leg for a quick single.
On off, Khawaja punches it right off the middle of the bat towards mid off.
Full again, around 141 clicks and speared into middle stump. Khawaja manages to keep it out.
Around the top of off, Khawaja leans back and taps it towards covers.
Fuller in length, angled into off. Khawaja blocks it off the front foot.
Naseem Shah is clocking really good speeds right from the off. This is bowled at 144.6 kph and on the off stump line. Usman Khawaja stays solid in defense though.
Naseem right away hits the hard length, outside off and there's a hint of reverse. Khawaja dabs it down towards cover-point.
Naseem Shah (5-1-12-0) is back into the attack. With the ball reversing, he will be quite potent with the ball.
Full again, around off. This is flicked towards mid-wicket.
FOUR! A bit too full and a bit too straight. Marnus Labuschagne gets down on one knee early and sweeps it fine. The ball runs away into the fine leg fence.
Floated up, full and outside off. Labuschagne reaches out to defend.
Short again, this is tucked away to short leg.
On a shorter length, around off. Usman Khawaja rocks back and opens up the face of the blade towards backward point for a run.
Usman Khawaja tries to get funky now. Slower and keeping low, outside off, Khawaja attempts the reverse sweep but gets no bat on it.
Fuller length, outside off and this one goes straight on. Labuschagne leaves it alone.

Past the outside edge again! Shaheen Afridi switches to 'round the wicket and angles it in from outside off. The ball reverses away a bit and Labuschagne has a poke at it. The ball zips past the outside edge. On the replay, UltraEdge confirms that there's no bat involved.
A length ball, angled across the off stump. Labuschagne has a slight shuffle past off stump and works it on the leg side.
Full and wide, stroked away nicely to the man at point.
A touch short and close to off, defended back off the back foot.
Fullish delivery, on the pads. Labuschagne tries to flick but misses. A good take by Rizwan.

DROPPED! It's all happening now out in the middle! Marnus Labuschagne is trying too many things and needs to be careful. This is down the leg side and Labuschagne looks to reverse sweep. He gets a top edge on it which loops up towards the point region. Nauman Ali over there is a bit lazy and just takes a couple of steps back but the ball goes over his head and he can only get fingertips on it. A big opportunity missed for Pakistan.
Uses his feet and works a full ball in the gap at mid-wicket for a run.
Flatter and close to off, Usman goes back in defense.
Around off, fuller in length, defended back.
Tossed up, around off, a conventional sweep from Marnus Labuschagne and he sends it down to fine leg for a single.

NOT OUT! Marnus Labuschagne just about gets away with it. Sliding into middle and leg, Labuschagne attempts the reverse sweep but gloves it down to Babar Azam at first slip. Labuschagne is out of his crease and Babar shows some sharp work as he throws it quickly onto the stumps. The umpire goes upstairs but the replays show that Labuschagne dragged his bat back in time.
Appeal for a run out...
Beaten! A length ball, outside off. Usman Khawaja looks to drive away from the body but there's a bit of movement and he is beaten past the outside edge.
On off and keeping a bit low. Well watched and well kept out by Khawaja.

Doesn't carry! Another good delivery from Shaheen Afridi. He hits the top of off, on a length and angles it in, the ball straightens and takes the outside edge of Khawaja's bat but doesn't carry to Mohammad Rizwan who dives to his left.
On off, kept out.

FOUR! Shaheen Afridi goes well wide of the crease and just about escapes a no ball call for cutting the return crease. This is a touch fuller and outside off. Khawaja just cuts it late past the slip cordon and picks up a boundary. That came off the bottom edge.

FIFTY! On a fuller length, outside off. Usman Khawaja opens the face of the blade and guides it past backward point. The batters come back for the second with ease and that will be fifty for Khawaja! Yet another solid knock from the batter of the series.
Sajid gives it more air and tosses it up fuller on middle stump. Khawaja uses his wrists to turn it through mid-wicket for one more. Labuschagne looks for the second run which isn't there.
On off, blocked out.
Loopy delivery, around off. Khawaja leans forward to defend.
Floated up, outside off. Marnus Labuschagne reaches out and sweeps it off the inner half of the blade towards deep square leg for one.
On middle and leg, worked through mid on for a single.
Tossed up, full and on middle. Khawaja blocks it out.
On a good length, close to the off pole. Labuschagne hangs back and defends it back onto the deck.
This is well outside off. Labuschagne makes an easy leave.
Well bowled! A touch fuller, outside off and angled in. This one straightens a bit after pitching and beats the outside edge of Labuschagne's willow. The ball dies on its way to the keeper as well.
Shaheen goes a bit wider of the crease and hurls across a good-length ball, around the sixth stump line. The ball comes in off the seam but Labuschagne keeps it out.
FOUR! Nicely worked! Full and angling back onto middle. Marnus Labuschagne keeps his balance and just times it beautifully through the gap in front of square on the leg side for a boundary.
Afridi hits the length bang on again and slants it in from around off. Labuschagne hangs back and dabs it out on the off side.
Floated up on middle. Khawaja blocks it out from his crease.
On middle, defended off the front foot.
Tossed up a bit, outside off.  Labuschagne reaches out and pushes it towards covers for a single.
On off, Labuschagne strides out to defend.

FOUR! Well, that's one way to get off a pair! Quicker and very full, around off. Marnus Labuschagne goes for the reverse sweep and gets it behind square on the off side. The ball races away to the third man fence. 100 up for Australia!
Sliding down the leg side, Khawaja tickles it 'round the corner and picks up a single.
Will Sajid Khan continue from this end? Yes, he is ready to bowl.

Beaten! Mohammad Rizwan doesn't seem interested and signals to not ask him and ask Fawad Alam at slip. Shaheen Afridi wants to press the issue maybe because they let go of one early on. This is fuller, on the sixth stump line. Labuschagne looks to hang back and drive but the ball zips past the outside edge. UltraEdge shows that there was no bat involved.
Still can't get off the mark! Slightly wider this time from Shaheen. Labuschagne pushes it towards the cover region.
Right on the money! The length is good again and this one is slanted into middle and leg. Labuschagne watchfully keeps it out.
Trivia - No team has batted for more than 107 overs in the fourth innings of a Test match at the Gaddafi Stadium in Lahore.
Afridi comes 'round the wicket to the right-hander. He bowls it full and angles it in from around off. Labuschagne digs it out on the off side.
Reverse swing straightaway! Length, around the top of off and nipping back in sharply. Khawaja works it behind square on the leg side for a single.
Afridi starts off the new session with a length delivery, wide outside off. The ball immediately keeps a bit low but Usman Khawaja manages to keep it out towards point.

We're back! The men concerned are also coming out in the middle. The first hour is going to be very critical and it very well could decide which way this Test match will go. Australia, of course, have the upper hand, but if Pakistan manage to force a collapse as they did on Day 2, that will throw this match wide open. Shaheen Afridi to bowl the first over of the afternoon...
... DAY 4, SESSION 2 ...

Pakistan appeared flat with their bowling in the initial phase. They leaked too many runs and failed to create much pressure in the morning. Although in the second half of the session, the hosts pulled things back a shade and brought the run rate down. It's surely reversing now and that will bring a different challenge for the Aussies. Pakistan's aim would be to utilize the conditions and restrict Australia's lead to under 300, if possible. A crucial session coming up and it will begin at 1.10 pm IST (7:40 am GMT). Do join us in a short while.

86 for 1 in 27 overs at a run rate of 3.19. A dominating morning session for Australia and they have extended their advantage! It was paramount for Pakistan to pick wickets and that too in a heap to stay in the hunt but they managed only one, minutes before Lunch, when Shaheen Afridi obliterated the off stump of David Warner. That was the only success for them and Australia have swelled their lead to 220 runs. The touring team batted with a run rate close to 5 in the first 30 minutes of the session but then slowed down. The intent though remained to score quickly and expect them to continue with the same plan.
Nicely flighted, around off. Labuschagne looks to sweep but gets it off the inside edge towards short leg and that will be Lunch on Day4!

How has that missed the off stump? Sajid Khan comes over the wicket for the right-hander and darts it in from outside off. The ball hits the rough and just turns back in sharply. Marnus Labuschagne makes the leave but is left a bit bamboozled there and maybe a bit lucky as well that the ball doesn't castle into the off stump.
Slower through the air, floated up and outside off. Khawaja squirts it towards point and picks up a single.
On middle, kept out.
Quicker one, at 93.8 kph and outside off. Usman Khawaja isn't going to play at that one.
Floated up, fuller and on middle. Khawaja pushes it out on the off side.
A yorker now, over 141 clicks and on the fifth stump line. Labuschagne digs it out on the off side.
Length again, at 143.5 kph and Labuschagne jams it out with hard hands towards the point region.
Fuller this time and wide of the off pole. The ball seams away a bit and Labuschagne leaves it alone.
On a length, angled into off and just straightening a touch again. Marnus Labuschagne hangs back and defends it out watchfully.
Shaheen goes quicker, well over 140 clicks but spills it way down leg. Mohammad Rizwan has to work hard again to reach it.
Marnus Labuschagne walks in next. He bagged a duck in the first innings and would look to make amends in his final outing with the bat on this tour.

OUT! Cleaned up! What a ripper of a delivery from Shaheen Afridi! Afridi angles it in around off, at 138 kph and this is on a perfect length as well. David Warner just hangs back and looks to get behind the line of the ball. The ball straightens after pitching and Warner is well beaten. The ball hits the off stump and sends it cartwheeling off the ground. On a closer look at the replays, we can detect some reverse swing with the shiny part of the ball inside. Warner played for the inward movement but perhaps it landed on one of the cracks or on the seam of the ball and went straight on. Not to be ashamed of if you get out to such deliveries. Afridi shakes hands with Warner as he walks off and the exciting contest between these two has come to an end. Australia lead by 219 runs.
On middle, use of feet again from Warner and he just eases it down the ground for a single.
Short and wide, David Warner rocks back to cut. The ball keeps a bit low and Warner gets a bottom edge on it.
Nicely tossed up again by Nauman Ali. Warner uses his feet but once again he can't get it past the inner ring on the off side.
Floated up, on the sixth stump line. Warner drives it straight to the man at extra cover.
A tad shorter and wider, Khawaja cuts it late behind point and picks up a single.
Quicker and fuller, outside off. Khawaja looks to cover-drive but gets beaten by the pace of the ball.
Back of a length, on the body. Khawaja tucks it down to fine leg for a single.
Fullish delivery, wide of the off stump. Khawaja looks to cut away from the body but is beaten past the outside edge.

David Warner does get to his fifty now and it's his second fifty of the series. On a good length, around off. Warner squeezes it off the back foot towards the cover region and scampers through for one. He has paced his innings really well so far and will be looking to score runs quickly now.
Warner is itching to get to his fifty now. Back of a length, around off. Warner stays deep in his crease and taps it towards short cover.
Back of a length, around off and reversing in a bit again. Warner keeps it out.
On a good length, around off and there's just a hint of reverse into the left-hander. Warner nudges it towards short cover.
Shaheen Afridi returns for another burst before Lunch. He has been quite expensive thus far, going for 32 runs in his 5.
Floated up, full and around off. Khawaja has a slight shuffle across off stump and goes deep in his crease to block it out.
Around off again, Usman Khawaja plays the dabbed reverse sweep and gets it behind point. The deep point fielder runs across and Khawaja picks up a brace.
Quicker again, around 90 clicks and close to the off pole. Khawaja keeps it out on the off side.
Quicker and fuller, outside off. Warner uses his feet again and strokes it towards long off for a single. He moves on to 49 now.

SIX! Aggressive cricket this from David Warner. Tossed up, right in the slot and it's off the rough as well. Warner gets down on one knee and slog-sweeps it all the way over the mid-wicket fence for a biggie.
David Warner comes down the pitch to the new bowler straightaway. Nauman Ali sees him coming though and slides one in quicker and a bit wider. Warner adjusts well to keep it out.
Change! Nauman Ali to have his first spell of the second innings.
Slower one, full and on middle at 117.4 kph, Usman shows the full face of the bat and defends it to mid on.
This one is pitching ahead of a fuller length, around off, Khawaja plays a mistimed on drive.
Fuller in length and on middle, Khawaja pushes it down the ground but finds the mid off fielder.
A bit short and around off, Khawaja remains on the back foot and tries to run it down to third man but finds backward point.
Fuller again, outside off, this time it has been driven from the middle of the bat but straight to the cover fielder.
Lands it full and outside off, Usman Khawaja tries to drive away from his body but gets a bottom edge.
Floated and on middle, Warner walks forward and defends it on the leg side.
Uses his feet and knocks a full ball down towards mid on for a single.
Eases a full ball in the gap at covers for one.
Full and flighted on off, defended to the off side.
FOUR! Bang! The length is pulled back by Sajid Khan, it's around off, Warner camps back and clobbers it through covers for a boundary.

Huge shout for an lbw from the bowler but he receives no support from his players. The umpire is unmoved. Tossed up, full and around off, Warner attempts to play the reverse-batted shot but misses. The replays show that he has been hit high on the forearm.
Full and on off, Usman flicks but finds mid-wicket.
Full and angling down the leg side, Usman tries to flick but misses and is hit on the pads. No appeal this time.
On a length around off, defended to the off side.

Shout for an lbw, not given and Babar Azam has taken the DRS. Hasan Ali gets a full ball to angle into the left-hander from around off. It stays quite low and strikes Khawaja on the back pad. Is it going down leg? The UltraEdge detects a spike and there is no need to look any further. The moment Pakistan players saw UltraEdge on the giant screen, they moaned collectively - 'ARRE...' Review lost for Pakistan.
Shortish again, outside off, David plays it down from the back foot to covers and crosses for a run this time. The lead is 200 now!
Fractionally short and close to off, Warner taps it down to cover-point and steps out for a run but then turns back.
Goes on the back foot to a short ball and punches it to sweeper cover for a single.
Fuller and off, pushed back to the bowler.
Loopy and on off, Warner jumps down the track and defends it back.
Floated and full, landing on middle, blocked on the leg side.
Short and outside off, Khawaja camps back and cuts it past backward point. Shaheen chases it down and saves one run for his team.
Flighted and around off, defended off the front foot.
Outside off, left alone.

What has happened there? David Warner is summoned by the umpires but he isn't sure what he has done wrong. The umpires are explaining to him that after he hits the ball, he is running onto the danger area of the pitch. Warner doesn't seem too happy about it and has a few words with the umpires. Babar Azam and Usman Khawaja too get into the conversation. Babar has a chat with Warner who continues to protest and Khawaja tries to explain to the umpires that Warner isn't doing much wrong here. The replays show that the issue is about the big stride forward Warner is putting after he plays the ball.
Spears in a very full ball on middle, Warner leans across and flicks it to mid-wicket.
Drifting down the leg side, Warner works it off his pads but finds the fielder in front of square on the leg side.
Pitches it up and around off, Warner leans forward and pushes it out to covers.
In the region outside off, on a good length, David allows it through to the keeper.
Starts the over by angling in a length ball on off, staying a touch low, Warner keeps his eyes on the ball and blocks it down.
This is darted into off. Khawaja blocks it out.
Flatter this time, but there's width on offer. Warner hangs back and steers it past backward point for a single.
A bit quicker and shorter, outside off. Warner cuts it off the back foot but straight to the man at point.
On off. Blocked.

FOUR! Cries of 'catch it' but it's well wide. Nicely tossed up around middle. David Warner is forced out of his crease and uses his wrists to flick it uppishly through the gap between mid on and mid-wicket for a boundary.
Nice and full, on middle. Warner defends it out.
Ali bowls this one a touch fuller and slants it in from around off. Khawaja defends it under his eye line. Hasan Ali starts off his new spell with a maiden.
Slightly shorter this time, around off. Khawaja hops onto the back foot and dabs it down towards the point region.
Keeping a fraction low again. On a nagging length, angling into off. Khawaja hangs back and blocks it out.
Full and outside off, Khawaja punches it towards covers from inside his crease.
And again! This is bowled way down the leg side, allowed through. Rizwan has to stay on his toes to move to his right and cut off the ball and stay wary of the double bounce as well.
Hasan Ali starts off with a gentle-paced delivery, spilling down the leg side. Khawaja looks to tickle it fine but misses.
Hasan Ali is back into the attack. 0/12 in his 3 overs so far.

Drinks break. It's been a rosy morning for Australia. They have scored runs with intent and a brisk rate - 56 in the first hour. The lead is stretched to 190 runs and Pakistan are getting cornered here. Apart from one moment when Naseem Shah breached the defense of Usman Khawaja off a no ball, the hosts have not looked penetrative enough. The shoulders also appear to drop now and they need to create a moment of brilliance to bounce back. Right now, it's one-way traffic.
Sajid bowls it a bit fuller and around off. Warner pushes it out towards the cover region.
Flighted this time, on middle. Warner leans forward and makes the block.
Good running again. On middle, eased towards mid on and the batters set off for the single really early.
Loopy delivery, on middle and leg. David Warner uses his feet to get to the pitch of the ball and pushes it towards mid on for a quick single.
Slightly tossed up, on middle and turning away a touch. Warner stays watchful in defense.
Around off, Warner strides out to defend.
Naseem goes full and attacks the off stump. Usman Khawaja solidly keeps it out from inside his crease.
Just a single this time. Angling into the pads, Warner looks to nudge it onto the leg side but the ball goes off the pads and behind square. They get a leg bye.
Close to the off stump line, Warner strides out to block but edges it down towards third man. The ball goes a bit wide of the man at third man and the batters come back for the second with ease.
Naseem Shah drags back his length a bit and slants it in from around the fifth stump line. Warner looks to defend off the front foot but gets it off the inner half of the bat.
Full and wide, at 140.5 kph. Warner squeezes it out towards point and shouts 'no run.'
Shah hurls across a full delivery, sliding into the pads. Warner defends it out with a straight bat.
Flatter this time, pushed through on off. Again the ball keeps a tad low but Khawaja gets his bat down in time.
This is full and on off. Khawaja digs it out back onto the deck.
Sajid gives it a bit more air and looks to turn it away from the leg stump line. Khawaja presses forward and pushes it towards mid on.
On the pads, tucked away behind square on the leg side for an easy single.
Flatter one, on the fourth stump line. This is pushed away onto the off side, off the back foot.
Nicely bowled! A touch of flight, dropping on a length and around off. Warner looks to come forward but has to adjust to keep it out.
Fuller this time, around off, Khawaja uses the angle of the bowler and clips it in the gap at deep mid-wicket for a brace.
Serves it on a good length and close to off, Usman presents a straight bat in defense.
Delivers it on a length and close to off, Warner gets forward to defend but it takes the inside edge and hurries behind square leg. They cross.
Around off, on a length and angling in, Warner sticks back and pushes it with an angled bat to point.
Finds the blockhole, Warner gets forward and defends it out from the bottom half of his blade.
Sliding down the leg side, Khawaja works a length ball to long leg for a run.
Fullish and on off, driven firmly to covers. Maiden!
Flatter and shorter around leg, Warner goes back and punches it down to mid on.
Loopy and full around middle, again it's defended back to the bowler, this time to his left.
Floated and full around off, defended back.
A touch short and on off, Warner gets back and cuts it to point.
Gets forward to a full ball and defends it to covers.
Full and around off, Usman has learnt from his mistake, gets forward and blocks it to the off side.
Leans forward and defends it to the cover region.
Fullish and on off, defended to mid on.
Around off, that is defended solidly off the front foot.

OUT OFF A NO BALL! What a reprieve for Usman Khawaja! Naseem Shah hurls across a length ball, landing around off and shaping back in sharply off the seam. It stays a bit low to beat the defense of Khawaja and destroys the stumps. Naseem celebrates on the face of the batter but soon finds out that he has overstepped.
Fuller and on off, angling in Usman Khawaja flicks it from the inner portion of his bat and it squirts in front of square leg. They collect two.
Angles in a full ball around off, Khawaja stays back and defends it around his pads to the leg side.
A touch flatter and shorter on off, Warner presses forward and then rocks back as he punches it to covers.
Fuller in length, again too straight from Sajid, Khawaja knocks it down to long off for a single.
Short and wide outside off, Usman Khawaja cuts but finds the fielder at backward point.
Clever batting. Khawaja again uses his feet to a full ball around middle and works it in the gap at mid-wicket for another couple.
Too full on this occasion, Usman plays a walking flick shot to deep mid-wicket for two. The 50-run stand comes up between Khawaja and Warner - third between them in this series.
Loopy and full around off, Usman Khawaja is forward in defense.
Fullish and around off, defended watchfully to mid-wicket.

Given how well the Aussie openers have started this morning, the missed opportunity on 5.3 could prove to be a big moment in the match. While watching it live, there was hardly a noise and Mohammad Rizwan didn't go up either but the replay shows that there was a faint edge off the toe end of the bat. Really difficult to judge in real time but given how close the ball was to the willow, there should have been at least some sort of appeal from the fielding side.
On a length again, around off and angling in, Usman takes the bottom hand off the handle as he works it down to long leg for a single.
Beaten! This one stays low. On a length and around off, angling in and staying low, Usman stays back to defend but it beats the inside half of his blade.
Goes fuller and on off, Khawaja drives it down the ground but finds mid on.
Warner does the same. Width there outside off, the length is a bit short and David eases it from the back foot to deep point for one.
Naseem begins with a short delivery, around off, Khawaja steers it through point and takes a single.
Naseem Shah (1-1-0-0) is into the attack. One slip and gully in place.
Slightly flighted, on middle. David Warner reaches out to defend this time.
On middle and leg, Warner defends it off the front foot.
A bit quicker, darted at the toes of the batter. Warner manages to keep it out.
On middle, Warner strides forward to defend.
This one slides down leg, Warner flicks it behind square on the leg side and picks up a couple of runs.
Good start from Sajid Khan! He spears one into middle from 'round the wicket. This is very full and Warner just about keeps it out.
Change in bowling. Sajid Khan comes into the attack. A slip and short leg in place. For how long will they last?
Full and slanted into middle. Khawaja stays solid in defense.
A touch fuller, angling in from wide of off stump. Khawaja looks to drive at it but gets beaten.

FOUR! Edgy boundary for Usman Khawaja but he'll take it. Bit of width on offer, Khawaja stays deep in his crease and looks to cut it late. The ball goes off the toe end of the bat and flies past a diving Fawad Alam at wide slip for another boundary. The runs have flown so far this morning.
Back of a length, close to the off pole. Warner stays leg-side of the ball and steers it to deep backward point for one more.
Around the top of off. Khawaja hangs back and plays it with an angled back through backward point for a run.
A length ball, over middle. Khawaja nudges it onto the leg side.
Switches back to 'round the wicket for Warner. Full and straight, blocked out.
Ali goes over the wicket and bowls it on the pads. Khawaja tucks it away to deep square leg for a single.
Full and wide, driven on the bounce towards the gully region.

FOUR! Everything going Australia's way at the moment. This is angled into middle, on a nagging length and Khawaja gets pushed onto the back foot. The ball keeps low but Khawaja just about manages to get his bat down in time. The ball takes the outside edge and goes through the slip cordon for another boundary. Hasan Ali doesn't look impressed.

Good cricket all around! On a driving length, outside off. David Warner gets a good stride forward and creams it past a diving extra cover fielder. Sajid Khan runs 'round from the cover fence and slides to his left to cut off the boundary. The batters do get three runs though.
Full, angled into middle but this one straightens. Warner watchfully keeps it out. Good bowling from Hasan Ali.
On a good length, on the fifth stump line. Warner hangs back and punches it away towards deep point for a single.
Another huge shout of 'no run' from David Warner. Afridi hist the length hard and bowls it on off stump. Warner taps it towards cover-point.
Around the top of off stump. David Warner gets pushed onto the back foot but solidly keeps it out.
Length, on off. Warner defends it off the front foot.
Shaheen goes fuller and angles it into middle and leg at around 140 clicks. Warner blocks it out from his crease and instantaneously shouts 'no run.'
Fullish length, around off. Khawaja strokes it through covers and rotates the strike.
Length again, over middle. Khawaja turns it in front of square on the leg side for a single. It's been easy for the Aussie batters at the moment.
Much better from Ali this time. Goes a bit fuller and slants it into middle stump. Khawaja gets right behind the line of the ball to make the block.
It's a bit too straight again from Hasan Ali and Warner is able to just work it 'round the corner to fine leg for one more. The lead is now 150!
Nicely bowled! A bit pitched up, in that channel around off and this one goes straight through. Warner has a poke at it but gets beaten past the outside edge.
Length ball, angled into the pads. Khawaja hangs back and just works it through mid-wicket for an easy single.
Ali slides this one down the leg side from 'round the wicket. Usman Khawaja gets a slight tickle on it. Mohammad Rizwan does well to dive down to his right and pouch the ball on the bounce.

FOUR! Third one of the over and Warner is making his intentions clear this morning. Shaheen Afridi once again digs in a short ball around off, David is ready on the back foot as he hammer-pulls it, this time in front of square on the leg side and it goes for a boundary. Expensive start from Shaheen!

FOUR! This one has gone like a rocket to the fence. Shaheen Afridi attempts to bounce out Warner but the Aussie opener is ready for the challenge. He rides the bounce and eases his pull shot through backward square leg. Timing is great and it speeds away to the fence in no time.
Pitches it up and around off, David leans across and works it towards mid on.

FOUR! Shot! David Warner at his very best. Back of a length, around off, Warner camps back and punches it sweetly through covers. It comes right from the middle of the bat and races away to the fence.

Around off, on a length and angling in, Warner defends it to the off side, takes a step forward and then shouts 'no-no'. Afridi immediately reacts, picks up the ball, turns and mimes a throw at Warner. Their friendly banter continues...
Shaheen begins Day 4 with a full ball on middle, Khawaja eases it to deep mid-wicket and takes a single.
Shaheen Afridi (2-0-11-0) to charge in from the opposite end.
Digs it in short and outside off, Warner goes on his toes and taps it down towards point. Looks for a run but it's not available.
Back of a length, around leg and angling down, Warner lets it be.
Full and outside off, going straight on, Warner leaves.

Hasan comes from 'round the wicket for Warner and delivers it a bit short outside off. David rocks back to cut but gets a bottom edge. It rolls closely past the stumps and Warner is alert to the situation as he moves back.
Australia are away on Day 4! Hasan bowls a length ball around leg, Khawaja opens up the field on the leg side with his shuffle across the stumps and clips it to deep square leg for a single.
First ball of the day is full and around off, angling away from the batter, Usman is on the front foot as he blocks it safely to the off side.

We are ready for play on Day 4! The overnight batters for Australia, Usman Khawaja and David Warner make their way out to the middle. The Pakistan players spread out on the field and it's going to be Hasan Ali to begin proceedings with the ball on Day 4. Let's go...

In the ongoing ICC Women's World Cup, things have really spiced up at the business end. The match between South Africa Women and West Indies was forced to be abandoned and both teams shared a point each. Courtesy of that one point, South Africa Women have qualified and also avoided facing Australia Women in the semi-final. In the other game, the defending champions are making a statement. England Women have steamrolled Pakistan Women for 105 and a win here will take them to 6 points, equal with India Women. Now, West Indies Women have played out all their league games and finished with 7 points. Their fate now lies in the outcome of the final game that India and England have in hand. The latter have Bangladesh Women next but for India Women, it's going to be a litmus test against South Africa Women.

The pitch has started to play tricks and we saw quite a few deliveries misbehaving. The bounce is inconsistent and there is a good amount of spin and reverse swing available too. Pakistan's chances at the moment look bleak but if they bowl to their potential this morning and pick a few quick wickets, they can stop Australia from running away with the show. Can the hosts turn up with full force? We will find out soon.

Welcome, ladies and gentlemen, for the fourth day of the final Test between Pakistan and Australia. After the first two days, it appeared that this match will also head towards a draw but powered by some great bowling by Starc and Cummins last evening, Australia have eased themselves in the driver's seat. The advantage lies with them and Day 4 is going to be all about extending it further. Can Pakistan stop them from doing that?

That concludes the proceedings for the day. We always use the term 'moving day' for Day 3 and this Test match has moved a long way in favour of Australia. All of a sudden, Pakistan find themselves on the back foot and will have to bowl really well on Thursday to have their say in this match. The first ball will be at 10.30 am IST (5 am GMT) but as usual, our build-up will begin in advance. Meanwhile, you can switch tabs to follow the final ODI - the decider - between South Africa and Bangladesh where the former have been reduced to 83/5 after electing to bat first. Cheers!

The Australian skipper says that they bowled really well in the first two sessions as well but didn't get the rewards and just needed to be a bit patient. Adds that the length was key and without much bounce in the pitch, they could just hit the 7-8 meter mark. Mentions that the last couple of hours have just flown by and they will look to build up a nice lead on Day 4. Ends by saying that it is great to bowl alongside Starc and also having someone like Nathan Lyon makes the job easier.

There was a little window of 3 overs for Australia to survive late in the day, and Usman Khawaja and David Warner successfully did that to complete an outstanding day of Test cricket for the touring team. They are now ahead by 134 runs and have a real shot at winning the series. Pat Cummins, who picked up the first 5-wicket haul by a pacer in this series, is up for a chat. Let's see what he has to say...

Australia's day on Pakistan Day. After two sessions, it appeared that both teams will share the honours but that was not meant to be. Azhar Ali and Abdullah Shafique's 150-run association would have been enough to deflate the confidence of any team but Australia showed great character and kept coming hard at the home team. Babar Azam also played a handy knock but once Fawad Alam was dismissed, the Pakistan innings nosedived. They lost their last 7 wickets for only 20 runs and conceded a 123-run lead.

Great things come from hard work and perseverance. Australia were ready to do the hard work on Day 3. They didn't get any success in the morning but hung in there and always kept their confidence high. Through sheer perseverance, they managed a couple of breakthroughs in the afternoon and eventually the door of fortunes opened for them in the second hour after the Tea break. The deadly duo of Mitchell Starc and Pat Cummins joined forces and wickets started to fall left, right and centre. They forced a collapse and ended up hunting down 9 wickets together.

David Warner fends off the final delivery from Shaheen Afridi and Australia will go into Day 4 with all 10 wickets intact! A length ball, around middle. Warner blocks it back onto the deck and shouts 'No' once again. Afridi comes up to him and both of them have a bit of a friendly banter. Australia are effectively 134/0 at Stumps on Day 4!
FOUR! This is pulled away nicely! Afridi bangs it in short again, around head height. David Warner takes it on and pulls it over square leg and picks up a boundary.

David Warner is itching to get off the mark but he seems a bit too eager. A length ball, on off. Warner taps it straight towards cover-point and sets off for a single. Usman Khawaja is a bit reluctant and sends him back.
Early cries of 'No' from David Warner. On middle, shaping away a touch. Warner punches it gently back past the bowler.
Short again, at 143.7 kph and angled down leg. Warner looks to pull but the ball doesn't rise up much again and zips past the bat.

Hostile delivery to get first up for David Warner. This is banged in short at 138.4 kph and angled at the body. Given it's a bouncer, Warner tries to duck under it. The ball doesn't bounce much and Warner gets hit on his back. That must have stung too!
Pitched up on off, Khawaja blocks it out from inside his crease.
Full and a bit wide this time. No shot offered by Khawaja.
Edged again! A touch fuller, tighter on off stump and at 140 clicks. Khawaja looks to cover-drive but gets a faint inside edge, which rolls towards the keeper. Good bowling this from Naseem Shah.

My word, that has nipped back in a long way! A length ball, outside off. This one hits the seam and just cuts back in sharply. Usman Khawaja makes an assured leave but the ball ends way down the leg side and it's a good take from Mohammad Rizwan behind the stumps.
This is fuller and on off. Khawaja drives it towards mid off.
Naseem Shah starts from 'round the wicket and pitches it up, on the fourth stump line. Usman Khawaja pushes it out towards covers.
Naseem Shah to operate from the opposite end.
Shorter this time, on the body. Khawaja hops and dabs it down through square leg. Imam-ul-Haq chases it down and slides in to save the boundary. Three runs taken.

FOUR! Sweetly timed! Pitched up on middle at 144 clicks. Usman Khawaja just pushes at it gently and strokes it through the mid-wicket region for a boundary. Khawaja and Australia are underway in this innings!

Doesn't carry! Afridi goes fuller, at 143.7 kph and angles it into middle and leg. Usman Khawaja plays at it with soft hands but gets an outside edge that goes low and lands well in front of the fielder at first slip.
This is nicely bowled into the channel around off. There is a bit of shape away from the left-hander and Khawaja leaves it alone.
Fullish delivery, around off. Khawaja drives it towards the cover region and calls 'no' straightaway.
Right on the money from Shaheen Afridi! Pitched up from over the wicket and on off. Usman Khawaja stays in his crease and solidly defends it out.

Pat Cummins is handed over the trophy and he celebrates the victory along with his teammates. Right then! That is it from this exuberant Test series! Australia has all the momentum as we now move to white-ball cricket. The three-match ODI series will begin on Tuesday, 29th March with the first ball to be bowled at 3:30 pm IST (10:00 am GMT). But as usual, the build-up will begin much earlier. Do join us for the same. Till then, it is goodbye from this side.

Pat Cummins, the skipper of Australia is the PLAYER OF THE MATCH for picking up a total of 8 wickets in the Test match. He says that it was fantastic the way they batted in the first innings and put themselves ahead in the game, and he thought 350 was a good enough target on this wicket. Mentions that the initial wickets were tough to get but once the ball was old and it started reversing it got better to take wickets. Adds that he is really happy with everyone's performance, and he is happy for Swepson as well, who was a key bowler for them. Concludes by saying that they have been well received in Pakistan and it has been a wonderful experience.

Babar Azam, the skipper of Pakistan, says that it was a great series. Adds that his side gave a good fight tthroughout the series but weren't good enough in the last two sessions on Day 5 of the third Test. Tells that they lost back-to-back wickets in the second session and that cost them. Mentions that they showed great character in the first two Tests but failed to get over the line in Lahore. He applauds the Australian team for the win and also thanks them for coming over to Pakistan after 24 years.

Usman Khawaja is the PLAYER OF THE SERIES for scoring 496 runs across three Tests! He says that they had a lot of fun playing in Pakistan, and he thanks all the Pakistani fans for showing all the support. He says that they have come a long way to play in Pakistan and it was fun. Mentions that they had a target of 350 in mind, as it was tough once the ball started reversing a bit and was confident of his side taking 10 wickets in four sessions. Concludes by saying that he felt that hundred in the last innings was one of the hardest hundreds he has scored.
... THE PRESENTATION ...

Pakistan conceded 391 runs with the ball in the first innings but their batters got them off to a great start as well. Abdullah Shafique, Azhar Ali and Babar Azam made some vital contributions but they completely fell apart when Pat Cummins and Mitchell Starc had their tail up with a relatively old ball. They lost wickets in quick succession and conceded a lead of 123 runs in the first innings. In the end, they were set a target of 351 and they did start well on Day 4, thanks to their openers, Abdullah Shafique and Imam-ul-Haq. However, apart from Babar Azam and Imam-ul-Haq, none of their batters managed to get in and score big and that cost them. Mohammad Rizwan didn't review when he was adjudged LBW and had he sent it upstairs, things could have been different for Pakistan. But having said that, Australia was just too good for Pakistan in this Test and they deserved to win this Test as well as the series.

Australia have dominated this Test match and they have justified their decision of declaring much earlier on Day 4. It was a combined effort from their batting department which set the tone for them in the first innings. Although, they were under the pump with the ball in the first innings, as Pakistan was cruising along at 248/3. But the duo of Mitchell Starc and Pat Cummins came roaring back and ensured that Australia get a handy lead in the first innings. Pakistan lost 7 wickets for just 20 runs and that proved to be the turning point in this Test. The Aussies piled on more runs with the bat in the second innings and it was Usman Khawaja who brought up his second century of the Test series. Australia set a target of 351 for Pakistan and their bowlers gave it their all on Day 5. The GOAT, Nathan Lyon grabbed a five-fer, which also included the prized scalp of Babar Azam. It was Pat Cummins who wrapped things up for his side and he finished with three wickets to his name.

WOW! What an end to this enthralling Test series. Australia are touring Pakistan after 24 long years, and they won the Benaud-Qadir Trophy 1-0. After a couple of draws at Rawalpindi and Karachi, Australia has managed to come out on top in Lahore. They have completely outclassed the hosts and the No.1 ranked Test side thoroughly deserves to win this three-match series. Pakistan would be proud of the way they played throughout the series but disappointed at the end of this game, as their openers toiled hard on Day 4 but they never looked like chasing down the target after losing Abdullah Shafique early on in the first session on Day 5.

OUT! CLEANED HIM UP! AUSTRALIA HAVE WON IN PAKISTAN! Pat Cummins brings himself into the attack and finishes things off in style! We finally have a result after 15 hard days of intense Test cricket. Coming to the ball - This was on a length, around middle, a straight delivery. Naseem Shah stays in the crease and looks to defend this but he misses and the ball goes on to shatter the stumps. Australia win by 115 runs!
Pat Cummins (15-6-23-2) brings himself into the attack.
On the pads, full in length. Nauman Ali works it away towards David Warner at short leg who collects the ball on the bounce.
Spinning in, around middle. Nauman Ali hangs back and blocks it out.
Loopy ball, around the leg pole. Nauman Ali defends it just away from the fielder at short leg.
Outside off, full, loopy delivery. Naseem Shah leans to block this, but the ball goes off the outside edge away from Steven Smith at first slip and towards third man. Single taken!
An appeal for LBW, but the umpire says no! A fuller ball, spinning in, around middle. Naseem Shah stays in the crease and looks to block this but the ball goes off the inside edge onto his pads.
Spinning in, shorter ball, around off. Naseem Shah defends it out off the back foot.
Tad shorter, on middle. Nauman Ali defends it back to the bowler.
Loopy ball, outside off, full in length. Nauman Ali blocks it out.
Outside off, full in length. Nauman Ali leans and drives it towards cover.
Fuller, outside off. Nauman Ali defends it out.

Two byes! Lovely delivery! That has missed everything! A loopy ball, spinning in, around middle and off. Nauman Ali leans to defend but he gets beaten on the inside edge. The ball goes over the middle pole and Alex Carey fails to grab the ball as well. It rolls behind towards fine leg and the batters steal in two byes!
Shorter ball, spinning in, outside off. Nauman Ali defends it out.
Tad shorter, around middle. Naseem Shah blocks it out solidly.
Full again, outside off. Naseem Shah leans and defends it out.
Beaten! Fuller ball, outside off, much straighter. Naseem Shah looks to defend but gets beaten on the outside edge.

OUT! CAUGHT! That is a terrific catch in the deep from Mitchell Swepson and Nathan Lyon bags a five-wicket haul. His second against Pakistan in Test cricket. Excellent effort from the GOAT and Pakistan lose their ninth wicket now. Lyon tosses it up, around off. Shaheen Afridi kneels and looks to slog-sweep it way over the deep square leg region. He miscues it to the left of Swepson in the deep who runs to his left, bends low and takes a really good catch. Naseem Shah is the last batter in. The Aussies are ecstatic and they get around Nathan Lyon to applaud him.
Commentary.Howout: c Mitchell Swepson b Nathan Lyon

Commentary.Commentary: Flatter and quicker, around middle. Shaheen Afridi rocks back in his crease and dabs it onto the deck.
This is bowled slower through the air, on a length, around leg. Shaheen Afridi keeps it out.
A low full toss, around middle and leg. Shaheen Afridi clips it behind square on the leg side for a single.
A full ball, way down leg. Shaheen Afridi misses his flick and the ball goes through to Alex Carey behind the sticks.
FOUR! BOOM! That is absolutely hammered by Shaheen Afridi! Starc bowls it full and outside off. Shaheen sits back and smashes it past the diving fielder at mid off for a cracking boundary.
Well bowled! Yorker-length delivery, around middle. Shaheen Afridi squeezes it out.
Another length delivery, outside off. Nauman Ali guides it past point for a single.
On a length, shaping away, outside off. Nauman Ali leaves it alone.

OUT! BOWLED! Oh, dear! Hasan Ali gets deceived by the turn and bounce here and that brings about his downfall of him. Lyon gets his man and Pakistan lose another wicket, their eighth to be precise. Lyon tosses this one up, well outside off. Hasan Ali looks to slog-sweep but he mistimes it completely and is a bit too early into his shot. He misses, the ball spins sharply and hits Hasan's helmet. It then ricochets off his glove and disturbs the stumps. Australia are just 2 wickets away from a series win. Shaheen Afridi walks out to bat now.
A loopy ball, on a length, outside off. Hasan Ali stretches forward and defends it.
Flatter and quicker, outside off. Hasan Ali blocks it off the front foot.
FOUR! Hasan Ali brings out the reverse-sweep this time! This is tossed up, outside off. Hasan kneels and reverse-sweeps it behind square on the off side for a boundary.
SIX! BANG! That came out of nowhere! Lyon serves a loopy ball, well outside off. Hasan Ali gets under it and dispatches it well over the long off fence for a maximum.
Tossed up delivery, outside off. Hasan Ali prods and defends it solidly.
A low full toss, around middle. Hasan Ali clips it wide of mid on and takes a single. He will retain the strike.
Back of a length, outside off. Hasan Ali lets it sail through to the keeper.
Good-length delivery, around off. Hasan Ali blocks it to the off side.
On a length, around middle. Hasan Ali tucks it to mid-wicket.

Another ball, full and outside off. Hasan Ali looks to dig it out. It takes the outside edge and runs away past the slip cordon. Mitchell Swepson at deep backward point, runs across to his left and keeps it to just two by diving to his left.
A full ball, well outside off. Hasan Ali lets it be.
Nicely tossed up, around middle. Nauman Ali defends it solidly. A maiden over from Nathan Lyon!
A wayward ball, down leg. Nauman Ali does not bother playing at that one.
Floated, on a length, around middle. Nauman Ali defends it off the front foot.
Lyon comes over the wicket now and serves it on a length, around leg. Nauman Ali gets forward to block but he misses and gets hit on his front pad.
Floated, full and outside off. Nauman Ali gets to the pitch of the ball and blocks it.
Flatter ball, around off. Nauman Ali defends it towards point.

NOT OUT! A huge appeal for caught behind but the umpire says no! Yorker-length delivery, outside off. Hasan Ali tries to dig this one out but he misses. Australia opt for a review after the umpire says no. UltraEdge shows that there is a gap between bat and ball. Hasan Ali survives and Australia lose their last review. A wicket-maiden from Mitchell Starc!
Outside off, shaping away, on a length. Hasan Ali leaves it alone.
A full ball, angling down leg, from 'round the wicket. Hasan Ali misses his flick and Alex Carey does well behind the sticks to grab it by diving to his left.
A short ball, angling in from outside off. Hasan Ali sways away from the line of the ball.
On a length, around off. Hasan Ali blocks it.
Hasan Ali is the new batter in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Another one bites the dust! Mitchell Starc gets rid of Sajid Khan who was looking well settled at the crease. He grabs his first wicket and Pakistan have lost their 7th wicket now. The hosts are falling apart here. A fuller ball, angling in, around middle. Sajid Khan flicks this but he was a bit early on his shot and ends up chipping it towards Usman Khawaja at mid-wicket. He pouches it safely and Sajid Khan walks back now. Australia are just 3 wickets away from a historic series win.
Commentary.Howout: c Usman Khawaja b Mitchell Starc

Commentary.Commentary: Floated, full and around off. Nauman Ali gets to the pitch of the ball and defends it.
Flighted ball, outside off. Nauman Ali blocks it off the front foot.
Lyon serves a loopy full toss, around off. Nauman Ali pushes it back to the bowler.
Nauman Ali walks out to bat.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! That's the wicket Australia were looking for and there is absolute silence at the Gaddafi stadium as Babar Azam walks back. Nathan Lyon strikes and grabs his third wicket. Pakistan are now 6 down. Australia do have this game in their pocket now. Coming to the ball - This was a full ball, much straighter on this occasion. Babar Azam leans to defend this but the ball goes off the outside edge towards first slip. Steven Smith there, who has dropped a few earlier, holds on to this one. He takes a sharp low catch towards his left.
Commentary.Howout: c Steven Smith b Nathan Lyon

Commentary.Commentary: Outside off, tad fuller. Sajid Khan opens the face of the bat and guides it towards point for a single.
Flatter ball, full, around off. Sajid Khan defends it out.

The second new ball has now been taken by Australia.

We are back for the final session of this Test series. The players have made their way out to the middle. Babar Azam and Sajid Khan will resume their innings. Mitchell Starc will start proceedings with the ball.
... Day 5, Session 3 ...

The equation is quite simple, Australia need 5 wickets to win this game and clinch the series, while Pakistan need 161 runs from 37 overs. A win here for Pakistan seems highly unlikely but they will come out and try to save this Test. An exciting final session coming up, which is set to begin at 3:50 pm IST (10:20 am GMT). Stay tuned!

Nathan Lyon began the proceedings by grabbing the big wicket of Imam-ul-Haq. Pat Cummins followed it up and struck twice in two overs and sent back Fawad Alam and Mohammad Rizwan. Reverse-swing is doing the trick for the Aussies and with the new ball now due, it will be interesting to see whether the Aussies opt for it straightaway. Pakistan, on the flip side are in a spot of bother. Babar Azam is leading by example, but there is no support whatsoever from the other end. Although, Babar was also given a life when Travis Head dropped a catch, just at the stroke of Tea.

Three big wickets in the session and just 54 runs were given away, it's safe to say that the second session belonged to the visitors. Pakistan will be under pressure now since Babar Azam is probably their last recognized batter and they have an uphill task ahead of them.
Flatter and quicker, outside off. Sajid Khan hangs back and taps it behind square on the off side. That will be Tea on Day 5!

They decide not to go for the review in the end. The replays show that the ball was very close to Babar's glove and there was a slight murmer on the UltraEdge as the ball passed the glove. Had Australia reviewed this, it would have been curtains for Babar Azam.

OUT! LBW! That is a peach of a delivery from the Aussie skipper and Mohammad Rizwan had absolutely no answers to that one. Huge, huge moment in this Test, and the Australians are pumped! Cummins runs in and serves a pinpoint yorker that angles in late. Rizwan is a bit late to react and he gets hit on his toe. Cummins appeals and the umpire agrees. Rizwan has a chat with his skipper but he doesn't opt for a review, he takes the long walk back to the pavilion. Although, the Ball Tracker shows that the impact was well outside off and had Rizwan taken the review he would be still out there in the middle. Nothing going Pakistan's way at the moment.

DRINKS! Australia has got a couple of wickets in quick succession right after the Lunch break and they are clearly in the driver's seat at the moment. To add to that, Pakistan have a long tail and it is now up to their two talismanic players, Babar Azam and Mohammad Rizwan to see their side home. Australia look favorites from hereon though. Mohammad Rizwan walks out to bat now.

The ball goes past his outside edge and hits him on the pad. The umpire raises his finger after an appeal for LBW from Australia. Fawad Alam opts for a review. The UltraEdge confirms no bat involved and the Ball Tracker shows three reds! Fawad Alam has to walk back. Pakistan lose a review as well.

OUT! CAUGHT! Lyon strikes straightaway after Lunch and this is a huge wicket for Australia! It is Imam-ul-Haq who has to walk back to the hut. Lovely bowling this from the GOAT and Pakistan find themselves in a spot of bother now. Lyon comes over the wicket and serves a flatter ball, on a length, around middle and spinning away late. Imam prods to block but it goes off the inside edge, onto the pad and the ball pops out towards Marnus Labuschagne at silly point who takes a sitter. Australia appeal and the umpire agrees. Imam opts for a review but the UltraEdge shows a clear spike as the ball passes the bat. Australia on top!

We are back for the post-Lunch session! The players stride out to the middle. Babar Azam and Imam-ul-Haq will resume their innings. Marnus Labuschagne will begin with the ball. A slip in place. Here we go...
... Day 5, Session 2 ...

This Test match is evenly poised at the moment with all three results still possible. The second session will give us a fair idea about where this Test match is heading. Do join us for the middle session which begins at 2 pm IST (8.30 am GMT).

Australia started the session well and it was Cameron Green who struck early by sending back Abdullah Shafique with a peach of a delivery. Starc and Cummins also kept bowling tight lines and lengths and did not allow the batters to free their arms. Lyon spun the ball sharply and he got the prized scalp of Azhar Ali. For Pakistan, Imam-ul-Haq has held one end and he batted well. Although, he will need to bat deep and make sure that he stitches a big partnership along with his skipper. They still need 215 runs to win and they cannot afford to lose wickets heading into the latter stages of this Test match.

Another riveting session of this Test match comes to an end. Australia would be happier of the two sides going into Lunch as they have got those two crucial wickets. Although, Pakistan have managed to score 63 runs from 33 overs in this session and they still have two in-form batters at the crease. The spinners though are getting a lot of turn off the surface and Pakistan's batters will need to be at their very best going ahead.
